{"timestamp": "2026-04-19T17:45:17.138642", "agent_name": "AstroDeepResearchAgent", "method_name": "load_cached_research", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "Cached research loaded from: deep_research_claude/Tyrosine-Run1.txt", "user_message": "Config: deep_research_claude", "raw_response": "# Prebiotic synthesis of tyrosine: the hardest amino acid to make from scratch\n\n**Tyrosine is among the most difficult proteinogenic amino acids to synthesize under prebiotic conditions, and no single-step prebiotic experiment has ever produced it directly from simple molecules.** The fundamental bottleneck is de novo aromatic ring formation \u2014 assembling a hydroxylated benzene ring from C\u2081\u2013C\u2082 feedstocks without enzymatic catalysis. Across six decades of prebiotic chemistry experiments, tyrosine has been absent from every standard spark discharge, hydrothermal simulation, and HCN polymerization experiment. Only two experimental approaches have yielded tyrosine: Friedmann and Miller's (1969) multi-step pathway via phenylacetylene intermediates, and Chen et al.'s (2008) UV photolysis of PAH-containing ices \u2014 both requiring preformed aromatic precursors. Thermodynamic analysis reveals why: tyrosine synthesis is strongly endergonic under surface conditions (**\u0394G = +334 kJ/mol** at 18\u00b0C, 1 atm) but becomes exergonic (**\u0394G = \u221260 kJ/mol**) at hydrothermal temperatures and pressures. This thermodynamic duality, combined with recent detection of tyrosine in pristine asteroid Bennu samples (2025) and abiotic aromatic amino acids in serpentinized ocean crust, suggests that hydrothermal and asteroidal environments are the most plausible settings for prebiotic tyrosine formation.\n\n---\n\n## Spark discharge experiments consistently fail to produce tyrosine\n\nThe foundational Miller-Urey experiment (Miller, 1953, *Science*) and all subsequent standard spark discharge experiments have failed to detect tyrosine among their products. The original 1953 experiment using CH\u2084/NH\u2083/H\u2082/H\u2082O detected only glycine, alanine, \u03b2-alanine, aspartic acid, and \u03b1-aminobutyric acid. Modern reanalysis of Miller's archived samples using HPLC and LC-ToF-MS (Johnson et al., 2008, *Science*; Parker et al., 2011, *PNAS*) expanded the detected amino acid inventory to **22\u201323 species** \u2014 but tyrosine remained conspicuously absent. The comprehensive Ring, Wolman, Friedmann, and Miller (1972, *PNAS*) electric discharge study confirmed 19+ amino acids with no aromatic amino acids detected whatsoever.\n\nThe single landmark positive result is Friedmann and Miller (1969, *Science*), who demonstrated phenylalanine and tyrosine synthesis through a deliberate **multi-step pathway** rather than one-pot discharge chemistry. Their route proceeded through: (1) generation of phenylacetylene from hydrocarbon pyrolysis/discharge; (2) radical addition of H\u2082S to phenylacetylene followed by hydrolysis to yield phenylacetaldehyde; (3) Strecker synthesis (phenylacetaldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 phenylalanine nitrile \u2192 phenylalanine). Tyrosine was obtained as a \"small yield\" side product, likely via hydroxylation during the H\u2082S-mediated step. Miller himself explicitly stated in subsequent reviews (1974, 1987) that \"the prebiotic synthesis of phenylalanine, tyrosine and tryptophan involves **pyrolysis reactions combined with plausible solution reactions**\" \u2014 acknowledging these aromatic amino acids require fundamentally different chemistry from the simple amino acids that form spontaneously in discharge experiments.\n\nEven experiments with different atmospheric compositions \u2014 neutral CO\u2082/N\u2082 atmospheres with oxidation inhibitors (Cleaves et al., 2008, *Origins Life Evol. Biosph.*), H\u2082S-rich volcanic gas mixtures (Parker et al., 2011, *PNAS*), and cyanamide-enriched systems (Parker et al., 2014, *Angewandte Chemie*) \u2014 consistently produced only aliphatic amino acids. The yield hierarchy in all spark discharge experiments follows: **glycine >> alanine > aspartic acid > aminobutyric acids > valine, leucine >> aromatic amino acids (not detected)**.\n\n---\n\n## UV photolysis and the PAH precursor requirement\n\nStandard UV photolysis experiments using simple ice mixtures (H\u2082O, CH\u2083OH, NH\u2083, CO, HCN) at 10\u201315 K produce glycine, alanine, serine, and a handful of other simple amino acids, but never tyrosine. Bernstein et al. (2002, *Nature*) and Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al. (2002, *Nature*) \u2014 the two seminal studies on amino acid formation in interstellar ice analogs \u2014 reported no aromatic amino acids. When Nuevo et al. (2008, *Origins Life Evol. Biosph.*) tentatively identified a tyrosine peak in VUV-irradiated ice residues, they retracted the claim, noting it was \"probably due to other compounds eluting from the column with the same retention times (coelution)\" and that \"the photoproduction of aromatic rings from aliphatic compounds is not an efficient process.\"\n\nThe critical exception is Chen et al. (2008, *Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society*), who irradiated **naphthalene** (C\u2081\u2080H\u2088, a polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon) mixed with H\u2082O and NH\u2083 ice at 15 K using synchrotron UV/EUV photons (4\u201320 eV). This experiment detected **13 amino acids including tyrosine and phenylalanine**. The key distinction is that the starting material already contained aromatic rings \u2014 the PAH served as a structural template, requiring only fragmentation and functionalization rather than de novo ring construction. Alanine was the most abundant product at **2.2 nmol**, with phenylalanine the dominant aromatic amino acid. This result demonstrates that wherever PAHs and ammonia coexist in icy environments exposed to UV radiation (interstellar clouds, cometary surfaces, outer solar system ices), aromatic amino acid formation is chemically feasible.\n\n---\n\n## Meteorite detections confirm extraterrestrial tyrosine formation\n\nThe history of tyrosine detection in meteorites traces a revealing arc from confident absence to confirmed presence. Early analyses of the Murchison meteorite (Kvenvolden et al., 1970, *Nature*; Engel and Nagy, 1982, *Nature*) explicitly reported tyrosine as absent, and its absence was used as evidence against terrestrial contamination \u2014 the logic being that biological contamination would introduce all common protein amino acids. Through the 1990s, meteorite amino acid inventories focused on C\u2082\u2013C\u2087 species, and tyrosine (a C\u2089 amino acid) fell outside the analytical window.\n\nAs methods improved and analyses extended to higher carbon numbers, tyrosine entered the comprehensive meteorite amino acid inventory. Glavin et al. (2018, Elsevier chapter) listed tyrosine among C\u2089 amino acids detected across multiple studies, and Elsila et al. (2016, *ACS Central Science*) confirmed that **12 of 20 protein amino acids have been found in meteorites, including tyrosine**. However, no individual concentration measurement for tyrosine in Murchison has been published \u2014 it is presumably at **sub-ppb to very low ppb levels**, orders of magnitude below glycine (~3,000 ppb) and \u03b1-aminoisobutyric acid (~1,000\u20136,000 ppb).\n\nThe strongest evidence for extraterrestrial tyrosine came in 2025 from NASA's OSIRIS-REx mission. Mojarro et al. (2025, *PNAS*) explicitly detected tyrosine in asteroid Bennu aggregates using pyrolysis-GC-MS with MRM mass spectrometry, confirmed by three independent transitions and analytical standards. Separately, Glavin et al. (2025, *Nature Astronomy*) reported tentative detection among **33 total amino acids** identified in Bennu samples, with overall racemic (D \u2248 L) composition supporting abiotic origin. Crucially, the Bennu team proposed that aromatic amino acids formed not via Strecker synthesis but through **Friedel-Crafts alkylation** of aromatic hydrocarbons during aqueous alteration on the parent body \u2014 a mechanism consistent with M\u00e9nez et al.'s (2018) findings in terrestrial serpentinites.\n\nRyugu samples (Hayabusa2) did not yield tyrosine, with amino acid detection limited to C\u2082\u2013C\u2086 species (Parker et al., 2023, *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta*; Naraoka et al., 2023, *Science*). No enantiomeric excess data exists specifically for tyrosine in any extraterrestrial sample.\n\n---\n\n## Hydrothermal vents offer thermodynamic viability but no experimental proof\n\n**No published hydrothermal vent simulation experiment has produced tyrosine.** Marshall (1994, *GCA*), Hennet et al. (1992, *Naturwissenschaften*), and Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2006, *Science*) all produced only simple amino acids (glycine, alanine, serine analogs). W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's iron-sulfur world framework, while demonstrating activated acetic acid, peptide formation, and simple amino acid synthesis on (Ni,Fe)S catalysts, explicitly does not extend to aromatic amino acid synthesis.\n\nHowever, thermodynamic calculations tell a strikingly different story. Amend and Shock (1998, *Science*) showed that amino acid synthesis from CO\u2082, H\u2082, NH\u2083, and H\u2082S becomes **thermodynamically favorable under hydrothermal conditions**. Higgs and Pudritz (2009, *Astrobiology*) compiled these data, showing tyrosine's Gibbs energy of formation shifts from **+334.20 kJ/mol at surface conditions (18\u00b0C, 1 atm)** to **\u221259.53 kJ/mol at hydrothermal conditions (100\u00b0C, 250 atm)**. This ~400 kJ/mol swing makes hydrothermal environments the only known setting where tyrosine synthesis is thermodynamically downhill.\n\nThe most compelling evidence for hydrothermal aromatic amino acid synthesis comes from M\u00e9nez et al. (2018, *Nature*), who discovered abiotic **tryptophan** preserved 173 meters below the seafloor in serpentinized rocks at the Atlantis Massif \u2014 the same geological setting as the Lost City hydrothermal field. The synthesis was attributed to **Friedel-Crafts reactions catalyzed by iron-rich saponite clay** during a late alteration stage. While tyrosine was not specifically identified, the same catalytic mechanism could plausibly generate it through analogous alkylation chemistry. Lost City conditions \u2014 **40\u2013116\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311**, rich in H\u2082 (up to 15 mM) and CH\u2084, with abundant iron-bearing minerals \u2014 appear optimal for both synthesis and preservation.\n\nBlack smoker vents (**300\u2013400\u00b0C, pH 2\u20135**) are far less favorable. Tyrosine decomposes rapidly above 200\u00b0C through decarboxylation (forming tyramine) and deamination. Sato et al. (2004, *Industrial & Engineering Chemistry Research*) measured phenylalanine (structurally analogous) decomposition at 200\u2013340\u00b0C/20 MPa with activation energy of **~154 kJ/mol**. At 250\u00b0C, aromatic amino acid half-lives are on the order of **minutes to hours**. The hydroxyl group on tyrosine's ring weakens the aromatic backbone compared to phenylalanine, making tyrosine particularly degradation-prone among aromatic amino acids (K\u00f6rner et al., 2021, *ChemSusChem*). One mitigating factor: dissolved H\u2082 suppresses amino acid decomposition (Lee et al., 2014), and dissolved metal salts at extreme pH may further inhibit degradation (Aspin et al., 2025, *GCA*).\n\n---\n\n## Mineral catalysts and the path through aromatic intermediates\n\nThe mineral catalysis landscape for tyrosine synthesis involves three distinct challenges: aromatic ring formation, functionalization to a phenylalanine/tyrosine precursor, and hydroxylation.\n\n**Iron-rich saponite clay** emerges as the most important catalyst for aromatic amino acid synthesis. M\u00e9nez et al. (2018, *Nature*) demonstrated it catalyzes Friedel-Crafts reactions producing tryptophan abiotically in serpentinized ocean crust. Saponite is a trioctahedral smectite clay abundant in serpentinites and carbonaceous chondrite parent bodies. Montmorillonite K10, a related acid clay, is a known industrial Friedel-Crafts catalyst, though it has not been specifically tested for prebiotic aromatic amino acid synthesis.\n\n**Iron oxyhydroxide minerals** (mixed-valence Fe(II)/Fe(III)) catalyze reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids under alkaline, moderate-temperature conditions. Barge et al. (2019, *PNAS*) demonstrated alanine synthesis from pyruvate at **50\u201370\u00b0C**, but this has not been extended to aromatic keto acid substrates like 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate. If 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate could be generated, its transamination to tyrosine on iron oxyhydroxide surfaces would be a plausible final step.\n\n**For aromatic ring formation**, acetylene cyclotrimerization (3 C\u2082H\u2082 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2086, \u0394G = \u2212142 kcal/mol) is catalyzed by multiple prebiotically available metals. Fe\u207a cations drive barrierless gas-phase cyclotrimerization (Shuman et al., Takahashi et al., 2022, *Molecules*). Ag(111) surfaces achieve **100% selective cyclotrimerization at temperatures as low as ~90 K** (2024, *Chemical Science*). Ni, Co, Cu, and Pd also catalyze this reaction. Acetylene itself is a plausible prebiotic molecule \u2014 it forms from methane pyrolysis and is explicitly included as a starting material in Patel et al.'s (2015) cyanosulfidic chemistry.\n\n**For hydroxylation** (benzene \u2192 phenol, or phenylalanine \u2192 tyrosine), the most relevant mineral systems are:\n\n- **TiO\u2082 photocatalysis**: Generates hydroxyl radicals (OH\u2022) under UV irradiation, well-established for aromatic ring hydroxylation in environmental chemistry but not yet demonstrated for Phe \u2192 Tyr specifically\n- **Fenton chemistry on iron minerals**: Fe\u00b2\u207a + H\u2082O\u2082 \u2192 OH\u2022 can hydroxylate aromatic rings. Mixed-valence iron minerals (magnetite, green rust) in vent systems could generate H\u2082O\u2082 via partial oxygen reduction\n- **ZnS photocatalysis**: Wang et al. (2012, 2013, *Origins Life Evol. Biosph.*; *Int. J. Astrobiology*) demonstrated UV-irradiated ZnS catalyzes reversible amination of \u03b1-keto acids, relevant to amino acid/keto acid interconversion but not tested for aromatic substrates\n\nPyrite (FeS\u2082) and mackinawite (FeS), while central to iron-sulfur world chemistry, have not demonstrated catalytic activity for aromatic ring formation. Their primary prebiotic roles remain electron transfer, surface adsorption, and simple carbon fixation (CO\u2082 \u2192 CO, N\u2082 \u2192 NH\u2084\u207a).\n\n---\n\n## The aromatic ring problem and cyanosulfidic chemistry's limits\n\nThe central unsolved problem in prebiotic tyrosine synthesis is constructing the aromatic ring from simple feedstocks. Modern biology uses the shikimate pathway \u2014 seven enzymatic steps converting phosphoenolpyruvate (PEP) and erythrose-4-phosphate (E4P) to chorismate, then additional steps to tyrosine via prephenate or arogenate. **No non-enzymatic version of this pathway has been demonstrated**, though individual steps show prebiotic potential. The chorismate \u2192 prephenate conversion is a Claisen rearrangement (a pericyclic reaction that proceeds thermally), and chorismate mutase merely accelerates it **~10\u2076-fold**. Coggins and Powner (2016, *Nature Chemistry*) achieved prebiotic synthesis of PEP \u2014 the highest-energy phosphate in biology and a shikimate pathway substrate \u2014 from glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde, providing one entry point.\n\nSutherland's cyanosulfidic chemistry (Patel et al., 2015, *Nature Chemistry*) represents the most sophisticated prebiotic synthesis network yet demonstrated, producing precursors for RNA, lipids, and amino acids from HCN, H\u2082S, and phosphate under UV irradiation with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling. However, it generates Strecker precursors for only **glycine, alanine, serine, and threonine** \u2014 all derivable from C\u2081\u2013C\u2083 aldehydes. **Neither Sutherland nor Powner has published a cyanosulfidic route to any aromatic amino acid.** The network provides PEP and sugar phosphates that could theoretically feed into a shikimate-like pathway, but the connection to aromatic ring assembly remains a critical gap.\n\nHCN polymerization produces complex mixtures containing some aromatic carbon (evidenced by \u00b9\u00b3C NMR resonances at 135\u2013142 ppm), but free aromatic amino acids have not been convincingly released from HCN polymer hydrolysis (Ferris et al., 1960s\u20131980s; Ruiz-Bermejo et al., 2021, *Processes*). The Diels-Alder [4+2] cycloaddition is a powerful ring-forming reaction (1,3-butadiene + dienophile \u2192 cyclohexene), but its application to prebiotic aromatic compound formation remains largely theoretical.\n\nBased on current evidence, the most plausible complete prebiotic pathway to tyrosine combines atmospheric/surface chemistry with aqueous processing:\n\n1. **CH\u2084 \u2192 C\u2082H\u2082** (acetylene) via spark discharge or pyrolysis\n2. **3 C\u2082H\u2082 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2086** (benzene) via metal-catalyzed cyclotrimerization\n3. **C\u2086H\u2086 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2085OH** (phenol) via radical hydroxylation (OH\u2022 from Fenton chemistry or UV photolysis)\n4. **Phenol + C\u2082 unit \u2192 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde** via Friedel-Crafts alkylation or radical addition\n5. **4-HPA + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 tyrosine** via Strecker synthesis\n\nThis is essentially the pathway implied by Friedmann and Miller (1969), combining high-energy atmospheric chemistry with aqueous solution chemistry. An alternative route proceeds through phenylalanine with a final hydroxylation step.\n\n---\n\n## Tyrosine ranks among the last amino acids in genetic code evolution\n\nTyrosine's prebiotic scarcity is mirrored in its late incorporation into the genetic code. Trifonov's consensus chronology (2000, *Gene*; 2004, *J. Biomol. Struct. Dynam.*), built from 40\u201382 independent criteria, ranks tyrosine **18th of 20** \u2014 preceded only by tryptophan. Higgs and Pudritz (2009, *Astrobiology*) classified tyrosine among the 10 \"late\" amino acids (Lys, Phe, Arg, His, Asn, Gln, Cys, Tyr, Met, Trp), with an observational concentration of **Crel = 0** \u2014 meaning it was never detected in any prebiotic synthesis experiment they surveyed. The 10 \"early\" amino acids (Gly, Ala, Asp, Glu, Val, Ser, Ile, Leu, Pro, Thr) have a mean formation energy of **169 \u00b1 42 kJ/mol**, while the late 10 average **285 \u00b1 94 kJ/mol**. Tyrosine at +334 kJ/mol exceeds even the late-group average.\n\nThe correlation between prebiotic availability and genetic code chronology is reinforced by biosynthetic cost data. Tyrosine requires **~50 ATP equivalents** for biological synthesis (Akashi and Gojobori, 2002, *PNAS*), compared to ~11.7 for glycine. Only tryptophan is more expensive at 74.3 ATP. Wong's coevolution theory (1975, 2005) proposes that late amino acids were added to the code as biosynthetic pathways evolved \u2014 consistent with tyrosine requiring the complex shikimate pathway, which could only emerge after sophisticated enzyme catalysis existed. Philip and Freeland (2011, *Astrobiology*) showed that 12 standard amino acids (including tyrosine) are not found in the Murchison meteorite and likely entered biology through metabolic innovation rather than environmental availability.\n\nRacemization rates present an additional challenge. Tyrosine, with its aromatic \u03b2-substituent facilitating \u03b1-proton abstraction, is among the most readily racemized amino acids (Bada and Schroeder, early 1970s). At 25\u00b0C and pH 7.6, racemization half-lives are **~10\u2075\u201310\u2076 years**, with Cu\u00b2\u207a ions accelerating rates ~100-fold. Any prebiotic enantiomeric excess from circularly polarized light or other asymmetric influences would be rapidly erased on geological timescales.\n\n---\n\n## Environmental synthesis map and the most plausible formation settings\n\nIntegrating all evidence, different prebiotic environments contribute to different steps of a hypothetical tyrosine synthesis network:\n\n| Synthesis step | Most favorable environment | Key evidence |\n|---|---|---|\n| Acetylene formation (CH\u2084 \u2192 C\u2082H\u2082) | Atmospheric discharge, volcanic lightning | Miller experiments, pyrolysis chemistry |\n| Benzene formation (3 C\u2082H\u2082 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2086) | Metal-rich mineral surfaces | Fe\u207a-catalyzed cyclotrimerization (Takahashi et al., 2022) |\n| Phenol formation (C\u2086H\u2086 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2085OH) | UV-exposed surface pools, Fenton chemistry | Radical hydroxylation at mineral-water interfaces |\n| Aromatic amino acid assembly | Serpentinite-hosted hydrothermal systems | Friedel-Crafts on Fe-rich saponite (M\u00e9nez et al., 2018) |\n| Strecker amino acid synthesis | Warm alkaline pools (~50\u201370\u00b0C) | Friedmann & Miller (1969) |\n| PAH \u2192 amino acid conversion | Asteroidal parent bodies, cometary ices | Chen et al. (2008); Bennu detection (Mojarro et al., 2025) |\n\n**Alkaline hydrothermal vents (Lost City type)** emerge as the thermodynamically optimal environment: moderate temperatures (40\u2013116\u00b0C), alkaline pH (9\u201311), H\u2082-rich fluids (suppressing decomposition), iron-bearing clay minerals for Friedel-Crafts catalysis, and favorable \u0394G for amino acid synthesis. **Exogenous delivery via carbonaceous meteorites and comets** provides a complementary source, with PAH-rich interstellar material undergoing UV processing and aqueous alteration to yield trace tyrosine alongside other amino acids. The detection of tyrosine in Bennu samples via Friedel-Crafts alkylation during aqueous alteration on the parent body validates this pathway.\n\nVolcanic/fumarolic environments contribute primarily to precursor generation \u2014 methane pyrolysis to acetylene, H\u2082S for thiol-mediated chemistry, and metal sulfide mineral surfaces. Surface evaporitic pools offer UV exposure for photochemistry and wet-dry cycling for concentration, but amino acid stability under UV is limited (Scappini et al., 2007, *Int. J. Astrobiology*).\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion: what remains unknown and what matters most\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis of tyrosine remains one of the outstanding challenges in origin-of-life chemistry, with several critical steps undemonstrated. **No experiment has achieved tyrosine synthesis from simple molecules (H\u2082O, CO\u2082, NH\u2083, HCN, CH\u2084) in a single continuous process.** The three most urgent open problems are: (1) demonstrating prebiotic benzene/phenol formation from C\u2081\u2013C\u2082 molecules under plausible conditions, not just thermodynamic favorability; (2) achieving regioselective para-hydroxylation of an aromatic ring without enzymatic catalysis; and (3) connecting cyanosulfidic or hydrothermal network chemistry to aromatic ring assembly.\n\nThe field has converged on two most-plausible formation scenarios. First, the **Friedmann-Miller atmospheric pathway**: methane discharge \u2192 acetylene \u2192 benzene (cyclotrimerization) \u2192 phenol (hydroxylation) \u2192 Strecker synthesis \u2192 tyrosine. Second, the **hydrothermal/asteroidal Friedel-Crafts pathway**: PAHs + ammonia + water undergo iron-clay-catalyzed alkylation to yield aromatic amino acids directly, as evidenced by M\u00e9nez et al.'s (2018) findings in serpentinites and the Bennu detection. These two routes are not mutually exclusive \u2014 atmospheric processing could generate aromatic precursors that are subsequently functionalized in aqueous hydrothermal systems.\n\nThe thermodynamic data provide perhaps the most actionable insight for future experimental work: tyrosine synthesis shifts from strongly endergonic to exergonic between surface and hydrothermal conditions, a **~400 kJ/mol swing** that represents the single largest thermodynamic leverage point. Experiments targeting tyrosine synthesis should therefore focus on **moderate hydrothermal conditions (50\u2013120\u00b0C, alkaline pH, H\u2082-rich) with iron-bearing clay catalysts** \u2014 the conditions where thermodynamics, mineral catalysis, and empirical evidence for abiotic aromatic amino acid formation most strongly converge. The recent demonstration that all 20 amino acid residues can be incorporated into prebiotically synthesized peptides (Foden et al., 2020, *Nature*) shows that once tyrosine is available, even at trace levels, it can be integrated into prebiotic protopeptide chemistry.", "parsed_response": {"source": "deep_research_claude/Tyrosine-Run1.txt", "config": "deep_research_claude", "length": 23032}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 0.0, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-19T17:45:17.141499", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Tyrosine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Tyrosine. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis of tyrosine: the hardest amino acid to make from scratch\n\n**Tyrosine is among the most difficult proteinogenic amino acids to synthesize under prebiotic conditions, and no single-step prebiotic experiment has ever produced it directly from simple molecules.** The fundamental bottleneck is de novo aromatic ring formation \u2014 assembling a hydroxylated benzene ring from C\u2081\u2013C\u2082 feedstocks without enzymatic catalysis. Across six decades of prebiotic chemistry experiments, tyrosine has been absent from every standard spark discharge, hydrothermal simulation, and HCN polymerization experiment. Only two experimental approaches have yielded tyrosine: Friedmann and Miller's (1969) multi-step pathway via phenylacetylene intermediates, and Chen et al.'s (2008) UV photolysis of PAH-containing ices \u2014 both requiring preformed aromatic precursors. Thermodynamic analysis reveals why: tyrosine synthesis is strongly endergonic under surface conditions (**\u0394G = +334 kJ/mol** at 18\u00b0C, 1 atm) but becomes exergonic (**\u0394G = \u221260 kJ/mol**) at hydrothermal temperatures and pressures. This thermodynamic duality, combined with recent detection of tyrosine in pristine asteroid Bennu samples (2025) and abiotic aromatic amino acids in serpentinized ocean crust, suggests that hydrothermal and asteroidal environments are the most plausible settings for prebiotic tyrosine formation.\n\n---\n\n## Spark discharge experiments consistently fail to produce tyrosine\n\nThe foundational Miller-Urey experiment (Miller, 1953, *Science*) and all subsequent standard spark discharge experiments have failed to detect tyrosine among their products. The original 1953 experiment using CH\u2084/NH\u2083/H\u2082/H\u2082O detected only glycine, alanine, \u03b2-alanine, aspartic acid, and \u03b1-aminobutyric acid. Modern reanalysis of Miller's archived samples using HPLC and LC-ToF-MS (Johnson et al., 2008, *Science*; Parker et al., 2011, *PNAS*) expanded the detected amino acid inventory to **22\u201323 species** \u2014 but tyrosine remained conspicuously absent. The comprehensive Ring, Wolman, Friedmann, and Miller (1972, *PNAS*) electric discharge study confirmed 19+ amino acids with no aromatic amino acids detected whatsoever.\n\nThe single landmark positive result is Friedmann and Miller (1969, *Science*), who demonstrated phenylalanine and tyrosine synthesis through a deliberate **multi-step pathway** rather than one-pot discharge chemistry. Their route proceeded through: (1) generation of phenylacetylene from hydrocarbon pyrolysis/discharge; (2) radical addition of H\u2082S to phenylacetylene followed by hydrolysis to yield phenylacetaldehyde; (3) Strecker synthesis (phenylacetaldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 phenylalanine nitrile \u2192 phenylalanine). Tyrosine was obtained as a \"small yield\" side product, likely via hydroxylation during the H\u2082S-mediated step. Miller himself explicitly stated in subsequent reviews (1974, 1987) that \"the prebiotic synthesis of phenylalanine, tyrosine and tryptophan involves **pyrolysis reactions combined with plausible solution reactions**\" \u2014 acknowledging these aromatic amino acids require fundamentally different chemistry from the simple amino acids that form spontaneously in discharge experiments.\n\nEven experiments with different atmospheric compositions \u2014 neutral CO\u2082/N\u2082 atmospheres with oxidation inhibitors (Cleaves et al., 2008, *Origins Life Evol. Biosph.*), H\u2082S-rich volcanic gas mixtures (Parker et al., 2011, *PNAS*), and cyanamide-enriched systems (Parker et al., 2014, *Angewandte Chemie*) \u2014 consistently produced only aliphatic amino acids. The yield hierarchy in all spark discharge experiments follows: **glycine >> alanine > aspartic acid > aminobutyric acids > valine, leucine >> aromatic amino acids (not detected)**.\n\n---\n\n## UV photolysis and the PAH precursor requirement\n\nStandard UV photolysis experiments using simple ice mixtures (H\u2082O, CH\u2083OH, NH\u2083, CO, HCN) at 10\u201315 K produce glycine, alanine, serine, and a handful of other simple amino acids, but never tyrosine. Bernstein et al. (2002, *Nature*) and Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al. (2002, *Nature*) \u2014 the two seminal studies on amino acid formation in interstellar ice analogs \u2014 reported no aromatic amino acids. When Nuevo et al. (2008, *Origins Life Evol. Biosph.*) tentatively identified a tyrosine peak in VUV-irradiated ice residues, they retracted the claim, noting it was \"probably due to other compounds eluting from the column with the same retention times (coelution)\" and that \"the photoproduction of aromatic rings from aliphatic compounds is not an efficient process.\"\n\nThe critical exception is Chen et al. (2008, *Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society*), who irradiated **naphthalene** (C\u2081\u2080H\u2088, a polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon) mixed with H\u2082O and NH\u2083 ice at 15 K using synchrotron UV/EUV photons (4\u201320 eV). This experiment detected **13 amino acids including tyrosine and phenylalanine**. The key distinction is that the starting material already contained aromatic rings \u2014 the PAH served as a structural template, requiring only fragmentation and functionalization rather than de novo ring construction. Alanine was the most abundant product at **2.2 nmol**, with phenylalanine the dominant aromatic amino acid. This result demonstrates that wherever PAHs and ammonia coexist in icy environments exposed to UV radiation (interstellar clouds, cometary surfaces, outer solar system ices), aromatic amino acid formation is chemically feasible.\n\n---\n\n## Meteorite detections confirm extraterrestrial tyrosine formation\n\nThe history of tyrosine detection in meteorites traces a revealing arc from confident absence to confirmed presence. Early analyses of the Murchison meteorite (Kvenvolden et al., 1970, *Nature*; Engel and Nagy, 1982, *Nature*) explicitly reported tyrosine as absent, and its absence was used as evidence against terrestrial contamination \u2014 the logic being that biological contamination would introduce all common protein amino acids. Through the 1990s, meteorite amino acid inventories focused on C\u2082\u2013C\u2087 species, and tyrosine (a C\u2089 amino acid) fell outside the analytical window.\n\nAs methods improved and analyses extended to higher carbon numbers, tyrosine entered the comprehensive meteorite amino acid inventory. Glavin et al. (2018, Elsevier chapter) listed tyrosine among C\u2089 amino acids detected across multiple studies, and Elsila et al. (2016, *ACS Central Science*) confirmed that **12 of 20 protein amino acids have been found in meteorites, including tyrosine**. However, no individual concentration measurement for tyrosine in Murchison has been published \u2014 it is presumably at **sub-ppb to very low ppb levels**, orders of magnitude below glycine (~3,000 ppb) and \u03b1-aminoisobutyric acid (~1,000\u20136,000 ppb).\n\nThe strongest evidence for extraterrestrial tyrosine came in 2025 from NASA's OSIRIS-REx mission. Mojarro et al. (2025, *PNAS*) explicitly detected tyrosine in asteroid Bennu aggregates using pyrolysis-GC-MS with MRM mass spectrometry, confirmed by three independent transitions and analytical standards. Separately, Glavin et al. (2025, *Nature Astronomy*) reported tentative detection among **33 total amino acids** identified in Bennu samples, with overall racemic (D \u2248 L) composition supporting abiotic origin. Crucially, the Bennu team proposed that aromatic amino acids formed not via Strecker synthesis but through **Friedel-Crafts alkylation** of aromatic hydrocarbons during aqueous alteration on the parent body \u2014 a mechanism consistent with M\u00e9nez et al.'s (2018) findings in terrestrial serpentinites.\n\nRyugu samples (Hayabusa2) did not yield tyrosine, with amino acid detection limited to C\u2082\u2013C\u2086 species (Parker et al., 2023, *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta*; Naraoka et al., 2023, *Science*). No enantiomeric excess data exists specifically for tyrosine in any extraterrestrial sample.\n\n---\n\n## Hydrothermal vents offer thermodynamic viability but no experimental proof\n\n**No published hydrothermal vent simulation experiment has produced tyrosine.** Marshall (1994, *GCA*), Hennet et al. (1992, *Naturwissenschaften*), and Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2006, *Science*) all produced only simple amino acids (glycine, alanine, serine analogs). W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's iron-sulfur world framework, while demonstrating activated acetic acid, peptide formation, and simple amino acid synthesis on (Ni,Fe)S catalysts, explicitly does not extend to aromatic amino acid synthesis.\n\nHowever, thermodynamic calculations tell a strikingly different story. Amend and Shock (1998, *Science*) showed that amino acid synthesis from CO\u2082, H\u2082, NH\u2083, and H\u2082S becomes **thermodynamically favorable under hydrothermal conditions**. Higgs and Pudritz (2009, *Astrobiology*) compiled these data, showing tyrosine's Gibbs energy of formation shifts from **+334.20 kJ/mol at surface conditions (18\u00b0C, 1 atm)** to **\u221259.53 kJ/mol at hydrothermal conditions (100\u00b0C, 250 atm)**. This ~400 kJ/mol swing makes hydrothermal environments the only known setting where tyrosine synthesis is thermodynamically downhill.\n\nThe most compelling evidence for hydrothermal aromatic amino acid synthesis comes from M\u00e9nez et al. (2018, *Nature*), who discovered abiotic **tryptophan** preserved 173 meters below the seafloor in serpentinized rocks at the Atlantis Massif \u2014 the same geological setting as the Lost City hydrothermal field. The synthesis was attributed to **Friedel-Crafts reactions catalyzed by iron-rich saponite clay** during a late alteration stage. While tyrosine was not specifically identified, the same catalytic mechanism could plausibly generate it through analogous alkylation chemistry. Lost City conditions \u2014 **40\u2013116\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311**, rich in H\u2082 (up to 15 mM) and CH\u2084, with abundant iron-bearing minerals \u2014 appear optimal for both synthesis and preservation.\n\nBlack smoker vents (**300\u2013400\u00b0C, pH 2\u20135**) are far less favorable. Tyrosine decomposes rapidly above 200\u00b0C through decarboxylation (forming tyramine) and deamination. Sato et al. (2004, *Industrial & Engineering Chemistry Research*) measured phenylalanine (structurally analogous) decomposition at 200\u2013340\u00b0C/20 MPa with activation energy of **~154 kJ/mol**. At 250\u00b0C, aromatic amino acid half-lives are on the order of **minutes to hours**. The hydroxyl group on tyrosine's ring weakens the aromatic backbone compared to phenylalanine, making tyrosine particularly degradation-prone among aromatic amino acids (K\u00f6rner et al., 2021, *ChemSusChem*). One mitigating factor: dissolved H\u2082 suppresses amino acid decomposition (Lee et al., 2014), and dissolved metal salts at extreme pH may further inhibit degradation (Aspin et al., 2025, *GCA*).\n\n---\n\n## Mineral catalysts and the path through aromatic intermediates\n\nThe mineral catalysis landscape for tyrosine synthesis involves three distinct challenges: aromatic ring formation, functionalization to a phenylalanine/tyrosine precursor, and hydroxylation.\n\n**Iron-rich saponite clay** emerges as the most important catalyst for aromatic amino acid synthesis. M\u00e9nez et al. (2018, *Nature*) demonstrated it catalyzes Friedel-Crafts reactions producing tryptophan abiotically in serpentinized ocean crust. Saponite is a trioctahedral smectite clay abundant in serpentinites and carbonaceous chondrite parent bodies. Montmorillonite K10, a related acid clay, is a known industrial Friedel-Crafts catalyst, though it has not been specifically tested for prebiotic aromatic amino acid synthesis.\n\n**Iron oxyhydroxide minerals** (mixed-valence Fe(II)/Fe(III)) catalyze reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids under alkaline, moderate-temperature conditions. Barge et al. (2019, *PNAS*) demonstrated alanine synthesis from pyruvate at **50\u201370\u00b0C**, but this has not been extended to aromatic keto acid substrates like 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate. If 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate could be generated, its transamination to tyrosine on iron oxyhydroxide surfaces would be a plausible final step.\n\n**For aromatic ring formation**, acetylene cyclotrimerization (3 C\u2082H\u2082 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2086, \u0394G = \u2212142 kcal/mol) is catalyzed by multiple prebiotically available metals. Fe\u207a cations drive barrierless gas-phase cyclotrimerization (Shuman et al., Takahashi et al., 2022, *Molecules*). Ag(111) surfaces achieve **100% selective cyclotrimerization at temperatures as low as ~90 K** (2024, *Chemical Science*). Ni, Co, Cu, and Pd also catalyze this reaction. Acetylene itself is a plausible prebiotic molecule \u2014 it forms from methane pyrolysis and is explicitly included as a starting material in Patel et al.'s (2015) cyanosulfidic chemistry.\n\n**For hydroxylation** (benzene \u2192 phenol, or phenylalanine \u2192 tyrosine), the most relevant mineral systems are:\n\n- **TiO\u2082 photocatalysis**: Generates hydroxyl radicals (OH\u2022) under UV irradiation, well-established for aromatic ring hydroxylation in environmental chemistry but not yet demonstrated for Phe \u2192 Tyr specifically\n- **Fenton chemistry on iron minerals**: Fe\u00b2\u207a + H\u2082O\u2082 \u2192 OH\u2022 can hydroxylate aromatic rings. Mixed-valence iron minerals (magnetite, green rust) in vent systems could generate H\u2082O\u2082 via partial oxygen reduction\n- **ZnS photocatalysis**: Wang et al. (2012, 2013, *Origins Life Evol. Biosph.*; *Int. J. Astrobiology*) demonstrated UV-irradiated ZnS catalyzes reversible amination of \u03b1-keto acids, relevant to amino acid/keto acid interconversion but not tested for aromatic substrates\n\nPyrite (FeS\u2082) and mackinawite (FeS), while central to iron-sulfur world chemistry, have not demonstrated catalytic activity for aromatic ring formation. Their primary prebiotic roles remain electron transfer, surface adsorption, and simple carbon fixation (CO\u2082 \u2192 CO, N\u2082 \u2192 NH\u2084\u207a).\n\n---\n\n## The aromatic ring problem and cyanosulfidic chemistry's limits\n\nThe central unsolved problem in prebiotic tyrosine synthesis is constructing the aromatic ring from simple feedstocks. Modern biology uses the shikimate pathway \u2014 seven enzymatic steps converting phosphoenolpyruvate (PEP) and erythrose-4-phosphate (E4P) to chorismate, then additional steps to tyrosine via prephenate or arogenate. **No non-enzymatic version of this pathway has been demonstrated**, though individual steps show prebiotic potential. The chorismate \u2192 prephenate conversion is a Claisen rearrangement (a pericyclic reaction that proceeds thermally), and chorismate mutase merely accelerates it **~10\u2076-fold**. Coggins and Powner (2016, *Nature Chemistry*) achieved prebiotic synthesis of PEP \u2014 the highest-energy phosphate in biology and a shikimate pathway substrate \u2014 from glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde, providing one entry point.\n\nSutherland's cyanosulfidic chemistry (Patel et al., 2015, *Nature Chemistry*) represents the most sophisticated prebiotic synthesis network yet demonstrated, producing precursors for RNA, lipids, and amino acids from HCN, H\u2082S, and phosphate under UV irradiation with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling. However, it generates Strecker precursors for only **glycine, alanine, serine, and threonine** \u2014 all derivable from C\u2081\u2013C\u2083 aldehydes. **Neither Sutherland nor Powner has published a cyanosulfidic route to any aromatic amino acid.** The network provides PEP and sugar phosphates that could theoretically feed into a shikimate-like pathway, but the connection to aromatic ring assembly remains a critical gap.\n\nHCN polymerization produces complex mixtures containing some aromatic carbon (evidenced by \u00b9\u00b3C NMR resonances at 135\u2013142 ppm), but free aromatic amino acids have not been convincingly released from HCN polymer hydrolysis (Ferris et al., 1960s\u20131980s; Ruiz-Bermejo et al., 2021, *Processes*). The Diels-Alder [4+2] cycloaddition is a powerful ring-forming reaction (1,3-butadiene + dienophile \u2192 cyclohexene), but its application to prebiotic aromatic compound formation remains largely theoretical.\n\nBased on current evidence, the most plausible complete prebiotic pathway to tyrosine combines atmospheric/surface chemistry with aqueous processing:\n\n1. **CH\u2084 \u2192 C\u2082H\u2082** (acetylene) via spark discharge or pyrolysis\n2. **3 C\u2082H\u2082 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2086** (benzene) via metal-catalyzed cyclotrimerization\n3. **C\u2086H\u2086 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2085OH** (phenol) via radical hydroxylation (OH\u2022 from Fenton chemistry or UV photolysis)\n4. **Phenol + C\u2082 unit \u2192 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde** via Friedel-Crafts alkylation or radical addition\n5. **4-HPA + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 tyrosine** via Strecker synthesis\n\nThis is essentially the pathway implied by Friedmann and Miller (1969), combining high-energy atmospheric chemistry with aqueous solution chemistry. An alternative route proceeds through phenylalanine with a final hydroxylation step.\n\n---\n\n## Tyrosine ranks among the last amino acids in genetic code evolution\n\nTyrosine's prebiotic scarcity is mirrored in its late incorporation into the genetic code. Trifonov's consensus chronology (2000, *Gene*; 2004, *J. Biomol. Struct. Dynam.*), built from 40\u201382 independent criteria, ranks tyrosine **18th of 20** \u2014 preceded only by tryptophan. Higgs and Pudritz (2009, *Astrobiology*) classified tyrosine among the 10 \"late\" amino acids (Lys, Phe, Arg, His, Asn, Gln, Cys, Tyr, Met, Trp), with an observational concentration of **Crel = 0** \u2014 meaning it was never detected in any prebiotic synthesis experiment they surveyed. The 10 \"early\" amino acids (Gly, Ala, Asp, Glu, Val, Ser, Ile, Leu, Pro, Thr) have a mean formation energy of **169 \u00b1 42 kJ/mol**, while the late 10 average **285 \u00b1 94 kJ/mol**. Tyrosine at +334 kJ/mol exceeds even the late-group average.\n\nThe correlation between prebiotic availability and genetic code chronology is reinforced by biosynthetic cost data. Tyrosine requires **~50 ATP equivalents** for biological synthesis (Akashi and Gojobori, 2002, *PNAS*), compared to ~11.7 for glycine. Only tryptophan is more expensive at 74.3 ATP. Wong's coevolution theory (1975, 2005) proposes that late amino acids were added to the code as biosynthetic pathways evolved \u2014 consistent with tyrosine requiring the complex shikimate pathway, which could only emerge after sophisticated enzyme catalysis existed. Philip and Freeland (2011, *Astrobiology*) showed that 12 standard amino acids (including tyrosine) are not found in the Murchison meteorite and likely entered biology through metabolic innovation rather than environmental availability.\n\nRacemization rates present an additional challenge. Tyrosine, with its aromatic \u03b2-substituent facilitating \u03b1-proton abstraction, is among the most readily racemized amino acids (Bada and Schroeder, early 1970s). At 25\u00b0C and pH 7.6, racemization half-lives are **~10\u2075\u201310\u2076 years**, with Cu\u00b2\u207a ions accelerating rates ~100-fold. Any prebiotic enantiomeric excess from circularly polarized light or other asymmetric influences would be rapidly erased on geological timescales.\n\n---\n\n## Environmental synthesis map and the most plausible formation settings\n\nIntegrating all evidence, different prebiotic environments contribute to different steps of a hypothetical tyrosine synthesis network:\n\n| Synthesis step | Most favorable environment | Key evidence |\n|---|---|---|\n| Acetylene formation (CH\u2084 \u2192 C\u2082H\u2082) | Atmospheric discharge, volcanic lightning | Miller experiments, pyrolysis chemistry |\n| Benzene formation (3 C\u2082H\u2082 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2086) | Metal-rich mineral surfaces | Fe\u207a-catalyzed cyclotrimerization (Takahashi et al., 2022) |\n| Phenol formation (C\u2086H\u2086 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2085OH) | UV-exposed surface pools, Fenton chemistry | Radical hydroxylation at mineral-water interfaces |\n| Aromatic amino acid assembly | Serpentinite-hosted hydrothermal systems | Friedel-Crafts on Fe-rich saponite (M\u00e9nez et al., 2018) |\n| Strecker amino acid synthesis | Warm alkaline pools (~50\u201370\u00b0C) | Friedmann & Miller (1969) |\n| PAH \u2192 amino acid conversion | Asteroidal parent bodies, cometary ices | Chen et al. (2008); Bennu detection (Mojarro et al., 2025) |\n\n**Alkaline hydrothermal vents (Lost City type)** emerge as the thermodynamically optimal environment: moderate temperatures (40\u2013116\u00b0C), alkaline pH (9\u201311), H\u2082-rich fluids (suppressing decomposition), iron-bearing clay minerals for Friedel-Crafts catalysis, and favorable \u0394G for amino acid synthesis. **Exogenous delivery via carbonaceous meteorites and comets** provides a complementary source, with PAH-rich interstellar material undergoing UV processing and aqueous alteration to yield trace tyrosine alongside other amino acids. The detection of tyrosine in Bennu samples via Friedel-Crafts alkylation during aqueous alteration on the parent body validates this pathway.\n\nVolcanic/fumarolic environments contribute primarily to precursor generation \u2014 methane pyrolysis to acetylene, H\u2082S for thiol-mediated chemistry, and metal sulfide mineral surfaces. Surface evaporitic pools offer UV exposure for photochemistry and wet-dry cycling for concentration, but amino acid stability under UV is limited (Scappini et al., 2007, *Int. J. Astrobiology*).\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion: what remains unknown and what matters most\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis of tyrosine remains one of the outstanding challenges in origin-of-life chemistry, with several critical steps undemonstrated. **No experiment has achieved tyrosine synthesis from simple molecules (H\u2082O, CO\u2082, NH\u2083, HCN, CH\u2084) in a single continuous process.** The three most urgent open problems are: (1) demonstrating prebiotic benzene/phenol formation from C\u2081\u2013C\u2082 molecules under plausible conditions, not just thermodynamic favorability; (2) achieving regioselective para-hydroxylation of an aromatic ring without enzymatic catalysis; and (3) connecting cyanosulfidic or hydrothermal network chemistry to aromatic ring assembly.\n\nThe field has converged on two most-plausible formation scenarios. First, the **Friedmann-Miller atmospheric pathway**: methane discharge \u2192 acetylene \u2192 benzene (cyclotrimerization) \u2192 phenol (hydroxylation) \u2192 Strecker synthesis \u2192 tyrosine. Second, the **hydrothermal/asteroidal Friedel-Crafts pathway**: PAHs + ammonia + water undergo iron-clay-catalyzed alkylation to yield aromatic amino acids directly, as evidenced by M\u00e9nez et al.'s (2018) findings in serpentinites and the Bennu detection. These two routes are not mutually exclusive \u2014 atmospheric processing could generate aromatic precursors that are subsequently functionalized in aqueous hydrothermal systems.\n\nThe thermodynamic data provide perhaps the most actionable insight for future experimental work: tyrosine synthesis shifts from strongly endergonic to exergonic between surface and hydrothermal conditions, a **~400 kJ/mol swing** that represents the single largest thermodynamic leverage point. Experiments targeting tyrosine synthesis should therefore focus on **moderate hydrothermal conditions (50\u2013120\u00b0C, alkaline pH, H\u2082-rich) with iron-bearing clay catalysts** \u2014 the conditions where thermodynamics, mineral catalysis, and empirical evidence for abiotic aromatic amino acid formation most strongly converge. The recent demonstration that all 20 amino acid residues can be incorporated into prebiotically synthesized peptides (Foden et al., 2020, *Nature*) shows that once tyrosine is available, even at trace levels, it can be integrated into prebiotic protopeptide chemistry.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Tyrosine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"The network follows the literature-supported view that tyrosine is not formed directly from simple prebiotic feedstocks in a single step, but instead emerges through multi-environment, multi-step chemistry centered on aromatic precursors. The primary routes implemented are: (i) the Friedmann-Miller style atmospheric/surface route in which methane pyrolysis/discharge yields acetylene, metal-catalyzed cyclotrimerization yields benzene, radical hydroxylation yields phenol, alkylation/oxidation yields 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde, and Strecker chemistry yields tyrosine; (ii) a phenylalanine-first branch followed by hydroxylation to tyrosine; and (iii) hydrothermal/asteroidal Friedel-Crafts-like routes in H2-rich serpentinizing systems using iron-bearing clays/minerals, consistent with M\u00e9nez et al. (2018) and Bennu interpretations. Because the literature emphasizes that aromatic ring construction is the bottleneck, the network uses acetylene, benzene, phenol, phenylacetaldehyde, 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde, and phenylalanine as key hubs linking Hydrothermal, Surface, and Biochemical environments. Ten distinct pathways are enumerated as alternative reaction sequences through the connected bipartite graph.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"methane\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethyne\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetylene\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H2/c1-2/h1-2H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H6\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"benzene\",\n      \"common_name\": \"benzene\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C6H6/c1-2-4-6-5-3-1/h1-6H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H6O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"phenol\",\n      \"common_name\": \"phenol\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C6H6O/c7-6-4-2-1-3-5-6/h1-5,7H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"HCN\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"H3N\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"oxidane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"sulfane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C8H8O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-phenylacetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"phenylacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C8H8O/c9-7-8-5-3-1-2-4-6-8/h1-7H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C9H11NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-phenylpropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"phenylalanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C9H11NO2/c10-8(9(11)12)6-7-4-2-1-3-5-7/h1-5,8H,6,10H2,(H,11,12)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C8H8O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-(4-hydroxyphenyl)acetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C8H8O2/c9-6-7-1-3-8(10)4-2-7/h1-4,6,10H,5H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C9H11NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-(4-hydroxyphenyl)propanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"tyrosine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C9H11NO3/c10-8(9(12)13)5-6-1-3-7(11)4-2-6/h1-4,8,11H,5,10H2,(H,12,13)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C8H6\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethynylbenzene\",\n      \"common_name\": \"phenylacetylene\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C8H6/c1-2-8-6-4-3-5-7-8/h1,3-7H\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C10H8\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"naphthalene\",\n      \"common_name\": \"naphthalene\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C10H8/c1-2-6-10-8-4-3-7-9(10)5-1/h1-8H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Methane pyrolysis/discharge to acetylene\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_002\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"molybdenite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"500-900K local pyrolytic zones; bulk ambient variable\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 (surface UV photocatalytic concentration) and sulfide mineral surfaces as environmental agents\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"volcanic lightning, discharge or pyrolysis; anoxic atmosphere\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"High-energy pyrolysis/discharge fragments methane to C2 hydrocarbons; acetylene accumulates as a reactive C2 building block.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step reflects the literature conclusion that acetylene is plausibly generated from methane by pyrolysis/discharge and serves as the entry point for aromatic ring construction, although mineral involvement is environmental rather than proven catalytic for this exact conversion. Included to connect the Friedmann-Miller atmospheric route under the required surface-mineral formalism; supported by Miller (1953), Friedmann & Miller (1969), Patel et al. (2015), and the synthesis map in the review. This step is partly speculative in its mineral assignment but not in the underlying pyrolytic chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetylene cyclotrimerization to benzene\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K on mineral surfaces; can occur over a wider range\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe-bearing mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"metal-rich dry volcanic or subaerial surfaces; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Three acetylene molecules undergo metal-mediated cyclotrimerization to form an aromatic benzene ring.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyclotrimerization of acetylene to benzene is a literature-highlighted solution to the aromatic ring problem and is thermodynamically favorable; Fe+ and other metals catalyze the process, making Fe-bearing mineral surfaces a plausible prebiotic analogue. This implements the recommended CH4 -> C2H2 -> C6H6 sequence. Supported by Takahashi et al. (2022) as summarized in the report, with broader metal-catalyzed cyclotrimerization evidence noted there; the exact use of elemental iron/magnetite as geochemical surface analogues is an informed extrapolation consistent with the review.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Radical hydroxylation of benzene to phenol\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and Fe redox-active mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation; OH radicals from photocatalysis or Fenton-like chemistry at mineral-water interfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-activated TiO2 and mixed-valence iron chemistry generate hydroxyl radicals that hydroxylate the aromatic ring, yielding phenol.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The review identifies radical hydroxylation of benzene to phenol at UV-exposed surface pools or Fenton-type mineral interfaces as the most plausible prebiotic route, while noting the step remains experimentally undemonstrated for the full tyrosine network. TiO2 photocatalysis is specifically cited as relevant to aromatic hydroxylation. Supported by the environmental chemistry framework summarized in the review and the hydroxylation discussion citing TiO2 photocatalysis and Fenton chemistry; this step is necessary but acknowledged as a key open problem.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Phenylacetylene to phenylacetaldehyde via H2S-mediated aqueous processing\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"molybdenite\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"radical addition of H2S followed by hydrolysis in anoxic solution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Phenylacetylene undergoes sulfur-mediated addition and hydrolytic conversion to phenylacetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reproduces the central intermediate conversion in the Friedmann-Miller multi-step route that produced phenylalanine and trace tyrosine from preformed aromatic precursors. The review states radical H2S addition to phenylacetylene followed by hydrolysis yields phenylacetaldehyde. Supported directly by Friedmann & Miller (1969); sulfide minerals are included as plausible environmental surfaces consistent with sulfur-rich prebiotic settings.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Benzene alkynylation to phenylacetylene\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-450K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe-bearing mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"high-energy volcanic or pyrolytic setting; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"A high-energy alkynylation/pyrolytic coupling step links benzene and acetylene to phenylacetylene.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Friedmann & Miller (1969) generated phenylacetylene from hydrocarbon pyrolysis/discharge chemistry rather than from a single defined low-temperature aqueous step. This reaction is included as a network connector representing that aromatic alkyne precursor generation from preformed aromatic hydrocarbons and acetylene-rich discharge chemistry. Supported conceptually by Friedmann & Miller (1969) and the review's summary of phenylacetylene arising from hydrocarbon pyrolysis/discharge; the exact surface-mediated formulation is a necessary abstraction.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of phenylalanine from phenylacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"molybdenite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay concentration surfaces with sulfide-rich chemistry\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"warm alkaline pools; Strecker synthesis followed by hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Phenylacetaldehyde reacts with HCN and NH3 to form an aminonitrile that hydrolyzes to phenylalanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the experimentally demonstrated aqueous solution step of the Friedmann-Miller pathway. The review states phenylacetaldehyde + HCN + NH3 gives phenylalanine nitrile and then phenylalanine. Supported directly by Friedmann & Miller (1969); general Strecker relevance is also consistent with classic prebiotic synthesis literature.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Phenol alkylation/oxidation to 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"saponite-like iron clay (represented by montmorillonite)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"313-389K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe-rich clay and Fe-S mineral assemblage\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline serpentinizing fluids, pH 9-11, H2-rich; Lost City-like\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"A Friedel-Crafts-like side-chain installation onto phenol, followed by aqueous oxidation/rearrangement, furnishes 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The review identifies Fe-rich saponite clay as the leading catalyst class for abiotic aromatic amino-acid-related Friedel-Crafts chemistry in serpentinites and asteroid parent bodies, and specifically proposes phenol + C2 unit -> 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde as part of the most plausible complete route. Supported by M\u00e9nez et al. (2018) for abiotic aromatic amino acid formation via iron-rich saponite, and by Mojarro et al. (2025) and Glavin et al. (2025) for Bennu interpretations invoking Friedel-Crafts alkylation during aqueous alteration. The exact substrate-level conversion to 4-HPA remains plausible rather than directly demonstrated.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct Strecker synthesis of tyrosine from 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"warm alkaline pools; Strecker aminonitrile formation followed by hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"4-Hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde undergoes Strecker addition with HCN and NH3 to give a tyrosine aminonitrile that hydrolyzes to tyrosine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The review explicitly identifies 4-HPA + HCN + NH3 -> tyrosine via Strecker synthesis as the most plausible terminal step in the atmospheric/surface route and notes Friedmann & Miller (1969) obtained tyrosine in small yield likely via hydroxylated aromatic intermediates. This reaction is therefore the literature-preferred direct route from a hydroxylated aromatic aldehyde to tyrosine. Supported by Friedmann & Miller (1969) and the synthesis-map interpretation in the review; direct isolated demonstration from purified 4-HPA is inferred but chemically standard.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydroxylation of phenylalanine to tyrosine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV-photocatalytic TiO2 and Fe redox-active surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation; OH radical chemistry; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Radical aromatic hydroxylation converts phenylalanine to para-hydroxylated tyrosine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The review names phenylalanine -> tyrosine hydroxylation as an alternative plausible route and notes that TiO2 photocatalysis and Fenton-like iron chemistry are the most relevant mineral systems for aromatic hydroxylation, though Phe -> Tyr has not yet been experimentally demonstrated prebiotically. Included as a literature-supported alternative path to the target and explicitly acknowledged as an open problem. Supported by the hydroxylation section of the review and by Friedmann & Miller (1969) indirectly through small-yield tyrosine alongside phenylalanine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Friedel-Crafts-like assembly of tyrosine from phenol, HCN and ammonia\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"saponite-like iron clay (represented by montmorillonite)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"250 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe-rich clay with Fe-S mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal fluids, pH 9-11, H2-rich; thermodynamically favorable for tyrosine formation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"In a condensed network representation, Fe-rich clay-catalyzed aromatic alkylation and nitrogen incorporation in alkaline hydrothermal fluids lead from hydroxylated aromatic precursors to tyrosine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction encodes the hydrothermal/asteroidal pathway favored by thermodynamics and by Bennu/serpentinite interpretations: aromatic hydrocarbons or phenolic precursors undergo Fe-clay-catalyzed Friedel-Crafts-like chemistry during aqueous alteration to yield aromatic amino acids. The review emphasizes tyrosine formation is exergonic at 100C/250 atm and that Fe-rich saponite catalysis in serpentinites is the strongest empirical analogue, although no exact tyrosine-forming vent simulation has yet been published. Supported by Amend & Shock (1998), Higgs & Pudritz (2009), M\u00e9nez et al. (2018), Mojarro et al. (2025), and Glavin et al. (2025). This is a literature-grounded but still partially speculative network-compression step.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"PAH photolysis to tyrosine in ammonia-water ice\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"15K ice photolysis followed by recovery to ambient handling; represented here as exogenous surface delivery context\",\n        \"pressure\": \"low to 1 atm equivalent after deposition\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral agents not required in original experiment; included here as surface deposition concentrators\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"synchrotron UV/EUV photons 4-20 eV; PAH-containing ices\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV/EUV irradiation of PAH-containing ammonia-water ices generates fragmented and functionalized aromatic organics including aromatic amino acids.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Chen et al. (2008) experimentally detected tyrosine and phenylalanine after UV/EUV irradiation of naphthalene/H2O/NH3 ice mixtures, demonstrating that preformed aromatic rings can be converted into aromatic amino acids. This is one of only two positive experimental routes highlighted in the review. Mineral agents are added only to satisfy the required schema for surface reactions and represent post-depositional concentration rather than the primary experimental catalyst; the core chemistry is directly supported by Chen et al. (2008).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"PAH photolysis to phenylalanine in ammonia-water ice\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"15K ice photolysis followed by deposition/recovery\",\n        \"pressure\": \"low to 1 atm equivalent after deposition\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface concentrator minerals only\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"synchrotron UV/EUV photons 4-20 eV; aromatic precursor already present\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV/EUV processing of PAH-containing ices yields aromatic amino acids including phenylalanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Chen et al. (2008) reported phenylalanine as the dominant aromatic amino acid in irradiated naphthalene/H2O/NH3 ices, providing an experimentally grounded branch into the phenylalanine -> tyrosine pathway. As with rxn_011, mineral agents are environmental placeholders required by the schema rather than the source of the experimental reactivity.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical Friedmann-Miller hydroxylated aldehyde route\",\n      \"description\": \"Methane-derived acetylene forms benzene, benzene is hydroxylated to phenol, hydrothermal Fe-clay chemistry yields 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde, and Strecker synthesis gives tyrosine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_002\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Phenylalanine-first atmospheric route\",\n      \"description\": \"Methane-derived aromatic chemistry proceeds through phenylacetaldehyde and phenylalanine, followed by aromatic hydroxylation to tyrosine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_002\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal direct phenol-to-tyrosine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface aromatic buildup to phenol is followed by hydrothermal Fe-clay-assisted direct assembly of tyrosine under favorable thermodynamic conditions.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_002\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"PAH ice direct delivery route\",\n      \"description\": \"Tyrosine is formed directly from naphthalene-containing ammonia-water ice under UV/EUV photolysis and then delivered to surface settings.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"PAH ice to phenylalanine then hydroxylation\",\n      \"description\": \"Photolyzed PAH ices furnish phenylalanine, which is subsequently hydroxylated in UV/mineral-rich surface pools to tyrosine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Benzene convergence to direct hydrothermal assembly\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetylene cyclotrimerization produces benzene, which after hydroxylation feeds directly into hydrothermal Fe-clay mediated tyrosine formation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Phenylacetylene branch to phenylalanine and tyrosine\",\n      \"description\": \"Benzene reacts further to phenylacetylene, sulfur-mediated aqueous processing gives phenylacetaldehyde, Strecker synthesis gives phenylalanine, and hydroxylation yields tyrosine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Phenol-to-4-HPA Strecker route starting from preformed benzene\",\n      \"description\": \"Where benzene is available exogenously or from prior surface chemistry, hydroxylation and Fe-clay alkylation generate 4-HPA for Strecker conversion to tyrosine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Phenol hub to dual-route tyrosine assembly\",\n      \"description\": \"Phenol acts as a hub from which either 4-HPA Strecker chemistry or direct hydrothermal Fe-clay chemistry can generate tyrosine; this pathway records the direct branch.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Mixed exogenous-endogenous hybrid route\",\n      \"description\": \"Exogenous PAH photochemistry yields phenylalanine while endogenous surface photochemistry yields hydroxylating conditions, producing tyrosine after surface processing.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_002\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": []\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Tyrosine", "overall_strategy": "The network follows the literature-supported view that tyrosine is not formed directly from simple prebiotic feedstocks in a single step, but instead emerges through multi-environment, multi-step chemistry centered on aromatic precursors. The primary routes implemented are: (i) the Friedmann-Miller style atmospheric/surface route in which methane pyrolysis/discharge yields acetylene, metal-catalyzed cyclotrimerization yields benzene, radical hydroxylation yields phenol, alkylation/oxidation yields 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde, and Strecker chemistry yields tyrosine; (ii) a phenylalanine-first branch followed by hydroxylation to tyrosine; and (iii) hydrothermal/asteroidal Friedel-Crafts-like routes in H2-rich serpentinizing systems using iron-bearing clays/minerals, consistent with M\u00e9nez et al. (2018) and Bennu interpretations. Because the literature emphasizes that aromatic ring construction is the bottleneck, the network uses acetylene, benzene, phenol, phenylacetaldehyde, 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde, and phenylalanine as key hubs linking Hydrothermal, Surface, and Biochemical environments. Ten distinct pathways are enumerated as alternative reaction sequences through the connected bipartite graph.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CH4", "iupac_name": "methane", "common_name": "methane", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "C2H2", "iupac_name": "ethyne", "common_name": "acetylene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2/c1-2/h1-2H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "C6H6", "iupac_name": "benzene", "common_name": "benzene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H6/c1-2-4-6-5-3-1/h1-6H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "C6H6O", "iupac_name": "phenol", "common_name": "phenol", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H6O/c7-6-4-2-1-3-5-6/h1-5,7H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CHN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "H3N", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "oxidane", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "sulfane", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C8H8O", "iupac_name": "2-phenylacetaldehyde", "common_name": "phenylacetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C8H8O/c9-7-8-5-3-1-2-4-6-8/h1-7H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C9H11NO2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-phenylpropanoic acid", "common_name": "phenylalanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C9H11NO2/c10-8(9(11)12)6-7-4-2-1-3-5-7/h1-5,8H,6,10H2,(H,11,12)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C8H8O2", "iupac_name": "2-(4-hydroxyphenyl)acetaldehyde", "common_name": "4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C8H8O2/c9-6-7-1-3-8(10)4-2-7/h1-4,6,10H,5H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C9H11NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-(4-hydroxyphenyl)propanoic acid", "common_name": "tyrosine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C9H11NO3/c10-8(9(12)13)5-6-1-3-7(11)4-2-6/h1-4,8,11H,5,10H2,(H,12,13)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C8H6", "iupac_name": "ethynylbenzene", "common_name": "phenylacetylene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C8H6/c1-2-8-6-4-3-5-7-8/h1,3-7H", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C10H8", "iupac_name": "naphthalene", "common_name": "naphthalene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C10H8/c1-2-6-10-8-4-3-7-9(10)5-1/h1-8H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Methane pyrolysis/discharge to acetylene", "inputs": ["mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_002"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "molybdenite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "500-900K local pyrolytic zones; bulk ambient variable", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 (surface UV photocatalytic concentration) and sulfide mineral surfaces as environmental agents", "aqueous": "false", "other": "volcanic lightning, discharge or pyrolysis; anoxic atmosphere"}, "mechanism": "High-energy pyrolysis/discharge fragments methane to C2 hydrocarbons; acetylene accumulates as a reactive C2 building block.", "reasoning": "This step reflects the literature conclusion that acetylene is plausibly generated from methane by pyrolysis/discharge and serves as the entry point for aromatic ring construction, although mineral involvement is environmental rather than proven catalytic for this exact conversion. Included to connect the Friedmann-Miller atmospheric route under the required surface-mineral formalism; supported by Miller (1953), Friedmann & Miller (1969), Patel et al. (2015), and the synthesis map in the review. This step is partly speculative in its mineral assignment but not in the underlying pyrolytic chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Acetylene cyclotrimerization to benzene", "inputs": ["mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K on mineral surfaces; can occur over a wider range", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Fe-bearing mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "false", "other": "metal-rich dry volcanic or subaerial surfaces; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Three acetylene molecules undergo metal-mediated cyclotrimerization to form an aromatic benzene ring.", "reasoning": "Cyclotrimerization of acetylene to benzene is a literature-highlighted solution to the aromatic ring problem and is thermodynamically favorable; Fe+ and other metals catalyze the process, making Fe-bearing mineral surfaces a plausible prebiotic analogue. This implements the recommended CH4 -> C2H2 -> C6H6 sequence. Supported by Takahashi et al. (2022) as summarized in the report, with broader metal-catalyzed cyclotrimerization evidence noted there; the exact use of elemental iron/magnetite as geochemical surface analogues is an informed extrapolation consistent with the review."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Radical hydroxylation of benzene to phenol", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and Fe redox-active mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation; OH radicals from photocatalysis or Fenton-like chemistry at mineral-water interfaces"}, "mechanism": "UV-activated TiO2 and mixed-valence iron chemistry generate hydroxyl radicals that hydroxylate the aromatic ring, yielding phenol.", "reasoning": "The review identifies radical hydroxylation of benzene to phenol at UV-exposed surface pools or Fenton-type mineral interfaces as the most plausible prebiotic route, while noting the step remains experimentally undemonstrated for the full tyrosine network. TiO2 photocatalysis is specifically cited as relevant to aromatic hydroxylation. Supported by the environmental chemistry framework summarized in the review and the hydroxylation discussion citing TiO2 photocatalysis and Fenton chemistry; this step is necessary but acknowledged as a key open problem."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Phenylacetylene to phenylacetaldehyde via H2S-mediated aqueous processing", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_008", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["molybdenite", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "radical addition of H2S followed by hydrolysis in anoxic solution"}, "mechanism": "Phenylacetylene undergoes sulfur-mediated addition and hydrolytic conversion to phenylacetaldehyde.", "reasoning": "This reproduces the central intermediate conversion in the Friedmann-Miller multi-step route that produced phenylalanine and trace tyrosine from preformed aromatic precursors. The review states radical H2S addition to phenylacetylene followed by hydrolysis yields phenylacetaldehyde. Supported directly by Friedmann & Miller (1969); sulfide minerals are included as plausible environmental surfaces consistent with sulfur-rich prebiotic settings."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Benzene alkynylation to phenylacetylene", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-450K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Fe-bearing mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "false", "other": "high-energy volcanic or pyrolytic setting; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "A high-energy alkynylation/pyrolytic coupling step links benzene and acetylene to phenylacetylene.", "reasoning": "Friedmann & Miller (1969) generated phenylacetylene from hydrocarbon pyrolysis/discharge chemistry rather than from a single defined low-temperature aqueous step. This reaction is included as a network connector representing that aromatic alkyne precursor generation from preformed aromatic hydrocarbons and acetylene-rich discharge chemistry. Supported conceptually by Friedmann & Miller (1969) and the review's summary of phenylacetylene arising from hydrocarbon pyrolysis/discharge; the exact surface-mediated formulation is a necessary abstraction."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Strecker synthesis of phenylalanine from phenylacetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "molybdenite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay concentration surfaces with sulfide-rich chemistry", "aqueous": "true", "other": "warm alkaline pools; Strecker synthesis followed by hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "Phenylacetaldehyde reacts with HCN and NH3 to form an aminonitrile that hydrolyzes to phenylalanine.", "reasoning": "This is the experimentally demonstrated aqueous solution step of the Friedmann-Miller pathway. The review states phenylacetaldehyde + HCN + NH3 gives phenylalanine nitrile and then phenylalanine. Supported directly by Friedmann & Miller (1969); general Strecker relevance is also consistent with classic prebiotic synthesis literature."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Phenol alkylation/oxidation to 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_002", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["saponite-like iron clay (represented by montmorillonite)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "313-389K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Fe-rich clay and Fe-S mineral assemblage", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline serpentinizing fluids, pH 9-11, H2-rich; Lost City-like"}, "mechanism": "A Friedel-Crafts-like side-chain installation onto phenol, followed by aqueous oxidation/rearrangement, furnishes 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde.", "reasoning": "The review identifies Fe-rich saponite clay as the leading catalyst class for abiotic aromatic amino-acid-related Friedel-Crafts chemistry in serpentinites and asteroid parent bodies, and specifically proposes phenol + C2 unit -> 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde as part of the most plausible complete route. Supported by M\u00e9nez et al. (2018) for abiotic aromatic amino acid formation via iron-rich saponite, and by Mojarro et al. (2025) and Glavin et al. (2025) for Bennu interpretations invoking Friedel-Crafts alkylation during aqueous alteration. The exact substrate-level conversion to 4-HPA remains plausible rather than directly demonstrated."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Direct Strecker synthesis of tyrosine from 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-343K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral concentration surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "warm alkaline pools; Strecker aminonitrile formation followed by hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "4-Hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde undergoes Strecker addition with HCN and NH3 to give a tyrosine aminonitrile that hydrolyzes to tyrosine.", "reasoning": "The review explicitly identifies 4-HPA + HCN + NH3 -> tyrosine via Strecker synthesis as the most plausible terminal step in the atmospheric/surface route and notes Friedmann & Miller (1969) obtained tyrosine in small yield likely via hydroxylated aromatic intermediates. This reaction is therefore the literature-preferred direct route from a hydroxylated aromatic aldehyde to tyrosine. Supported by Friedmann & Miller (1969) and the synthesis-map interpretation in the review; direct isolated demonstration from purified 4-HPA is inferred but chemically standard."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Hydroxylation of phenylalanine to tyrosine", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV-photocatalytic TiO2 and Fe redox-active surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation; OH radical chemistry; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Radical aromatic hydroxylation converts phenylalanine to para-hydroxylated tyrosine.", "reasoning": "The review names phenylalanine -> tyrosine hydroxylation as an alternative plausible route and notes that TiO2 photocatalysis and Fenton-like iron chemistry are the most relevant mineral systems for aromatic hydroxylation, though Phe -> Tyr has not yet been experimentally demonstrated prebiotically. Included as a literature-supported alternative path to the target and explicitly acknowledged as an open problem. Supported by the hydroxylation section of the review and by Friedmann & Miller (1969) indirectly through small-yield tyrosine alongside phenylalanine."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Hydrothermal Friedel-Crafts-like assembly of tyrosine from phenol, HCN and ammonia", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_002", "mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["saponite-like iron clay (represented by montmorillonite)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "373K", "pressure": "250 atm", "catalyst": "Fe-rich clay with Fe-S mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline hydrothermal fluids, pH 9-11, H2-rich; thermodynamically favorable for tyrosine formation"}, "mechanism": "In a condensed network representation, Fe-rich clay-catalyzed aromatic alkylation and nitrogen incorporation in alkaline hydrothermal fluids lead from hydroxylated aromatic precursors to tyrosine.", "reasoning": "This reaction encodes the hydrothermal/asteroidal pathway favored by thermodynamics and by Bennu/serpentinite interpretations: aromatic hydrocarbons or phenolic precursors undergo Fe-clay-catalyzed Friedel-Crafts-like chemistry during aqueous alteration to yield aromatic amino acids. The review emphasizes tyrosine formation is exergonic at 100C/250 atm and that Fe-rich saponite catalysis in serpentinites is the strongest empirical analogue, although no exact tyrosine-forming vent simulation has yet been published. Supported by Amend & Shock (1998), Higgs & Pudritz (2009), M\u00e9nez et al. (2018), Mojarro et al. (2025), and Glavin et al. (2025). This is a literature-grounded but still partially speculative network-compression step."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "PAH photolysis to tyrosine in ammonia-water ice", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_006", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "15K ice photolysis followed by recovery to ambient handling; represented here as exogenous surface delivery context", "pressure": "low to 1 atm equivalent after deposition", "catalyst": "mineral agents not required in original experiment; included here as surface deposition concentrators", "aqueous": "true", "other": "synchrotron UV/EUV photons 4-20 eV; PAH-containing ices"}, "mechanism": "UV/EUV irradiation of PAH-containing ammonia-water ices generates fragmented and functionalized aromatic organics including aromatic amino acids.", "reasoning": "Chen et al. (2008) experimentally detected tyrosine and phenylalanine after UV/EUV irradiation of naphthalene/H2O/NH3 ice mixtures, demonstrating that preformed aromatic rings can be converted into aromatic amino acids. This is one of only two positive experimental routes highlighted in the review. Mineral agents are added only to satisfy the required schema for surface reactions and represent post-depositional concentration rather than the primary experimental catalyst; the core chemistry is directly supported by Chen et al. (2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "PAH photolysis to phenylalanine in ammonia-water ice", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_006", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "15K ice photolysis followed by deposition/recovery", "pressure": "low to 1 atm equivalent after deposition", "catalyst": "surface concentrator minerals only", "aqueous": "true", "other": "synchrotron UV/EUV photons 4-20 eV; aromatic precursor already present"}, "mechanism": "UV/EUV processing of PAH-containing ices yields aromatic amino acids including phenylalanine.", "reasoning": "Chen et al. (2008) reported phenylalanine as the dominant aromatic amino acid in irradiated naphthalene/H2O/NH3 ices, providing an experimentally grounded branch into the phenylalanine -> tyrosine pathway. As with rxn_011, mineral agents are environmental placeholders required by the schema rather than the source of the experimental reactivity."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Canonical Friedmann-Miller hydroxylated aldehyde route", "description": "Methane-derived acetylene forms benzene, benzene is hydroxylated to phenol, hydrothermal Fe-clay chemistry yields 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde, and Strecker synthesis gives tyrosine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_007", "rxn_008"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_002", "mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Phenylalanine-first atmospheric route", "description": "Methane-derived aromatic chemistry proceeds through phenylacetaldehyde and phenylalanine, followed by aromatic hydroxylation to tyrosine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_005", "rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_002", "mol_003", "mol_013", "mol_009", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Hydrothermal direct phenol-to-tyrosine route", "description": "Surface aromatic buildup to phenol is followed by hydrothermal Fe-clay-assisted direct assembly of tyrosine under favorable thermodynamic conditions.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_002", "mol_003", "mol_004"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "PAH ice direct delivery route", "description": "Tyrosine is formed directly from naphthalene-containing ammonia-water ice under UV/EUV photolysis and then delivered to surface settings.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "PAH ice to phenylalanine then hydroxylation", "description": "Photolyzed PAH ices furnish phenylalanine, which is subsequently hydroxylated in UV/mineral-rich surface pools to tyrosine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_012", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Benzene convergence to direct hydrothermal assembly", "description": "Acetylene cyclotrimerization produces benzene, which after hydroxylation feeds directly into hydrothermal Fe-clay mediated tyrosine formation.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_004"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Phenylacetylene branch to phenylalanine and tyrosine", "description": "Benzene reacts further to phenylacetylene, sulfur-mediated aqueous processing gives phenylacetaldehyde, Strecker synthesis gives phenylalanine, and hydroxylation yields tyrosine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_005", "rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_013", "mol_009", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Phenol-to-4-HPA Strecker route starting from preformed benzene", "description": "Where benzene is available exogenously or from prior surface chemistry, hydroxylation and Fe-clay alkylation generate 4-HPA for Strecker conversion to tyrosine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_007", "rxn_008"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Phenol hub to dual-route tyrosine assembly", "description": "Phenol acts as a hub from which either 4-HPA Strecker chemistry or direct hydrothermal Fe-clay chemistry can generate tyrosine; this pathway records the direct branch.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Mixed exogenous-endogenous hybrid route", "description": "Exogenous PAH photochemistry yields phenylalanine while endogenous surface photochemistry yields hydroxylating conditions, producing tyrosine after surface processing.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_012", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_002", "mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_010", "mol_011"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_003", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_002"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_003", "rxn_005"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_004", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_003"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_007", "rxn_010"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_010", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_006", "rxn_012"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_009"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_011", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_007"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_008"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_012", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "