     \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C9H8O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"4-hydroxy-2-oxo-3-phenylpropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"4-hydroxyphenylpyruvic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C9H8O4/c10-6-3-1-5(2-4-6)7(11)8(12)9(13)14/h1-4,10H,(H,13,14)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Methane pyrolysis/discharge to acetylene\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_002\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"high-energy volcanic lightning / pyrolytic regime; local hot zones consistent with discharge and pyrolysis chemistry\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 (surface photocatalytic concentrator) and sulfide minerals as surface energy-transducing minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic atmosphere; volcanic discharge/pyrolysis context; acetylene explicitly identified as plausible prebiotic product from methane pyrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Energetic fragmentation/dehydrogenation of methane under discharge or pyrolysis conditions generates C2 hydrocarbons including acetylene, which are captured on nearby mineral surfaces.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Acetylene formation from methane in atmospheric discharge/pyrolysis is part of the Friedmann-Miller logic and is identified in the review as the first plausible step toward aromatic amino acids; Patel et al. also explicitly included acetylene as a prebiotic starting material in cyanosulfidic chemistry. Exact mineral catalysis for this step is not the main literature focus, but a surface mineral agent is required by schema, so TiO2 and sulfide minerals are included as plausible environmental agents rather than as uniquely demonstrated catalysts. Supported by Miller (1953), Friedmann & Miller (1969), Patel et al. (2015); use of mineral agents here is a necessary network connection and therefore partly speculative.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Atmospheric/discharge generation of hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"high-energy discharge regime\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide minerals as concentrating/photoredox mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic atmosphere; UV and electrical discharge exposure\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Electric discharge and photochemical processing of reduced C/N gases forms HCN, which later participates in Strecker and cyanosulfidic chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN is a standard prebiotic product in discharge chemistry and is central to Strecker and cyanosulfidic pathways used in the literature discussion. Aromatic amino acids are not made directly in one-pot discharge experiments, but HCN remains an essential precursor. Supported by Miller (1953), Ring et al. (1972), Patel et al. (2015). Mineral agents are environmental concentrators required by the schema and are not meant to imply a uniquely demonstrated catalytic necessity for HCN formation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetylene cyclotrimerization to benzene on metal-rich mineral surfaces\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-450K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and elemental iron\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"metal-rich surface; anoxic; cyclotrimerization step representing literature-supported aromatic ring construction from acetylene\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Three acetylene molecules adsorb to Fe-bearing mineral surfaces and undergo cyclotrimerization to a benzene ring.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The review identifies acetylene cyclotrimerization as the key non-enzymatic route to aromatic ring formation and notes Fe+-catalyzed barrierless cyclotrimerization and prebiotically available metal catalysts for this chemistry. Because the allowed hydrothermal minerals are Fe-based, magnetite and Fe0 are used as the closest network-compliant mineral analogues. Supported conceptually by Takahashi et al. (2022) and the broader aromatic ring discussion in the review; exact prebiotic vent demonstration on magnetite/Fe0 is still indirect, so this step should be regarded as literature-guided but not experimentally identical.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Benzene hydroxylation to phenol at UV-exposed mineral-water interfaces\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation; hydroxyl-radical generation at mineral-water interface; anoxic surface pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"TiO2 under UV irradiation generates reactive hydroxyl species that hydroxylate benzene to phenol on illuminated wet mineral surfaces.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The review specifically identifies TiO2 photocatalysis as the most relevant mineral system for aromatic hydroxylation in prebiotic surface settings, while noting lack of direct demonstration for tyrosine-specific hydroxylation. This step is therefore a literature-aligned bridge from benzene to phenol and is less speculative than phenylalanine-to-tyrosine hydroxylation. Supported by the review's synthesis map and environmental chemistry logic; grounded in TiO2 photocatalytic aromatic hydroxylation literature as summarized there, with prebiotic application still partly speculative.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Phenylacetylene formation from acetylene-rich discharge/pyrolysis mixtures\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_002\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"hot pyrolytic/discharge regime\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals and TiO2 as mineral surfaces in volcanic/discharge settings\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic; intended to represent phenylacetylene emergence from pyrolysis/discharge mixtures rather than a single clean synthetic laboratory transformation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aryl-ethynyl coupling is represented here as net generation of phenylacetylene from acetylene-rich aromatic discharge products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Friedmann & Miller (1969) require phenylacetylene as the key aromatic precursor, and the review emphasizes that phenylacetylene should be treated as originating from hydrocarbon pyrolysis/discharge mixtures rather than via an overconfident clean synthetic step. This reaction is therefore explicitly a network abstraction for that experimentally motivated precursor pool, not a claim of a single demonstrated mineral-catalyzed elementary reaction. Supported by Friedmann & Miller (1969), Miller (1974), Miller (1987); necessary abstraction flagged as partially speculative.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"H2S-mediated conversion of phenylacetylene to phenylacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous sulfur-rich pool; hydrolysis after sulfur addition\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Phenylacetylene undergoes sulfur-mediated radical/addition chemistry followed by hydrolysis to yield phenylacetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step directly follows the Friedmann-Miller route in which H2S addition to phenylacetylene followed by hydrolysis gives phenylacetaldehyde, the immediate Strecker precursor to phenylalanine. The review notes tyrosine likely appeared as a small-yield side product during related sulfur-mediated chemistry. Supported by Friedmann & Miller (1969); mineral surface assignment uses sulfur-rich surface minerals to satisfy schema and reflect volcanic sulfur-rich settings.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydroxylated sulfur-mediated conversion to 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals with UV-exposed TiO2 surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"sulfur-rich aqueous pool; UV-assisted oxidative functionalization; intended to capture the small-yield hydroxylated side-product logic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sulfur-mediated transformation of phenylacetylene is coupled to partial oxidative/hydroxylating chemistry, yielding para-hydroxylated phenylacetaldehyde as a minor branch.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The review states that in Friedmann & Miller (1969), tyrosine was obtained in small yield likely via hydroxylation during the H2S-mediated stage. The direct identity of 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde as the branching intermediate is implied by the broader synthesis map rather than demonstrated explicitly, so this reaction is literature-guided but speculative. Supported by Friedmann & Miller (1969) and the review's proposed complete pathway; speculative status acknowledged.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Phenylacetaldehyde Strecker synthesis to phenylalanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and phosphate minerals as concentrating surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"warm aqueous pool; Strecker-type amino acid synthesis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The aldehyde forms an aminonitrile with HCN and NH3, followed by hydrolysis to phenylalanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the core solution-phase step of the Friedmann-Miller aromatic amino acid route. Supported directly by Friedmann & Miller (1969), with warm aqueous Strecker conditions consistent with the review's environmental map. Mineral agents are added as plausible concentrating surfaces required by schema.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"4-Hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde Strecker synthesis to tyrosine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"warm alkaline pool; Strecker-type pathway from hydroxylated aromatic aldehyde\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"A hydroxylated aromatic aldehyde undergoes Strecker addition with HCN and NH3 to the corresponding aminonitrile, followed by hydrolysis to tyrosine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The review's most plausible complete pathway ends with 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde + HCN + NH3 leading to tyrosine via Strecker synthesis, explicitly identified as the route implied by Friedmann & Miller (1969) and the broader synthesis map. This is therefore the strongest explicit endgame to tyrosine in the network, though the precursor 4-HPA remains underdemonstrated. Supported by Friedmann & Miller (1969) and the review's concluding pathway summary.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"PAH photolysis in H2O/NH3 ice yielding aromatic amino acids including tyrosine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"15 K irradiation phase followed by warming/residue recovery\",\n        \"pressure\": \"low pressure ice/vacuum analog\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and clay used here only as environmental mineral analogs for deposition/concentration after delivery\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"UV/EUV irradiation of naphthalene + H2O + NH3 ice; exogenous/ice-photolysis branch feeding planetary surface chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV/EUV photolysis fragments and functionalizes a preformed aromatic PAH framework, generating amino-acid-containing refractory residues including phenylalanine and tyrosine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Chen et al. (2008) is one of only two experimental demonstrations yielding tyrosine, and crucially it starts from naphthalene in H2O/NH3 ice under synchrotron UV/EUV irradiation. This reaction is included exactly because the literature requires preformed aromatic precursors for successful tyrosine generation. Surface mineral agents here represent post-delivery concentration and schema compliance, not the original ice photolysis catalyst. Supported directly by Chen et al. (2008).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fe-clay/Friedel-Crafts-type assembly from phenol to 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"313-389K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe-rich mineral/clay analogue represented by greigite and pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Lost City-like alkaline conditions; pH 9-11; H2-rich serpentinite-hosted setting; thermodynamically favorable regime for tyrosine-related synthesis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Phenol is alkylated/functionalized by a two-carbon unit under Fe-rich mineral catalysis to give a para-hydroxylated aromatic aldehyde precursor.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The review identifies this as the most plausible but still undemonstrated bridge in the complete tyrosine pathway: phenol + C2 unit -> 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde via Friedel-Crafts alkylation or radical addition. M\u00e9nez et al. (2018) demonstrated abiotic aromatic amino acid formation via Fe-rich saponite-catalyzed Friedel-Crafts chemistry in serpentinites, and Mojarro et al. (2025) proposed Friedel-Crafts alkylation during aqueous alteration on Bennu parent material. Because saponite is not in the allowed mineral list, greigite/pyrite are used as Fe-rich hydrothermal proxies; this step remains explicitly speculative but literature-motivated. Supported by M\u00e9nez et al. (2018), Mojarro et al. (2025), Glavin et al. (2025); speculative connection acknowledged.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal carbon fixation to pyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions; H2-rich serpentinization-driven system\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Successive mineral-catalyzed reductions and C-C bond-forming steps fix CO2 into an alpha-keto acid pool represented here by pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The system instructions require inclusion of hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis as a key reaction type and it provides a realistic keto-acid feed into later amination chemistry. While not tyrosine-specific, this hydrothermal hub is important for environmental interconnection and for anchoring the alpha-keto-acid chemistry discussed by Barge et al. Supported by the vent chemistry framework in Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1997, 2006), Amend & Shock (1998), and by the problem framing that hydrothermal conditions favor amino acid formation thermodynamically; exact pyruvate synthesis details remain broader vent-network chemistry rather than tyrosine-specific experimental proof.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fe-mediated conversion of 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde to 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"323-389K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal fluid; H2-rich; keto-acid generating branch\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Net oxidation/carboxylating transformation of the aromatic aldehyde gives the corresponding alpha-keto acid 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The review highlights 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate as a plausible aromatic keto-acid substrate for final amination on iron oxyhydroxide surfaces, but notes that generating this substrate prebiotically is unresolved. This reaction is therefore a necessary connector, not a directly demonstrated prebiotic experiment. It is included explicitly as speculative but motivated by the Barge-style reductive amination logic and the centrality of aromatic keto acids in biological tyrosine biosynthesis. Supported indirectly by Barge et al. (2019) for keto-acid amination chemistry and by the review's discussion of 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate as a plausible precursor; speculative status acknowledged.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination/transamination of 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate to tyrosine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"323-343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe-bearing mineral surfaces functioning as iron oxyhydroxide analogues\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline pH 9-11; H2-rich moderate hydrothermal system; Lost City-like temperatures preferred to avoid aromatic amino acid decomposition\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The aromatic alpha-keto acid undergoes mineral-surface reductive amination or transamination to the amino acid tyrosine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Barge et al. (2019) demonstrated reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on iron minerals at 50-70C, and the review identifies 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate -> tyrosine on iron oxyhydroxide surfaces as a plausible final step not yet experimentally extended to aromatic substrates. This is therefore a literature-guided but unproven hydrothermal endgame, included because the review explicitly singles it out as one of the most plausible final transformations under alkaline moderate-temperature conditions. Supported by Barge et al. (2019), Amend & Shock (1998), Higgs & Pudritz (2009); aromatic substrate extension remains speculative.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent pH gradient; H2-rich serpentinization context\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 is reduced by H2 on Fe-S minerals to formate, building a reduced carbon pool for hydrothermal organosynthesis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The system instructions require CO2 reduction on greigite to formate as a canonical hydrothermal process, and the deep research report emphasizes hydrothermal thermodynamic favorability for amino acid synthesis generally. Although not tyrosine-specific, formate supports the hydrothermal reducing environment underpinning aromatic precursor elaboration. Supported by Amend & Shock (1998), Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1997, 2006), and the vent-chemistry framework summarized in the report.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Friedmann-Miller hydroxylated side-branch route\",\n      \"description\": \"Classical multi-step aromatic route: methane-derived acetylene feeds phenylacetylene formation, sulfur-mediated hydroxylated aromatic aldehyde formation, then Strecker synthesis to tyrosine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_002\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyclotrimerization-then-hydroxylation route to Strecker tyrosine\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface methane pyrolysis generates acetylene, hydrothermal Fe minerals cyclotrimerize it to benzene, surface UV/TiO2 hydroxylates to phenol, hydrothermal Fe-rich chemistry converts phenol to 4-HPA, then Strecker synthesis gives tyrosine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"r