le": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Methane pyrolysis/discharge to acetylene", "inputs": ["mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_002"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "high-energy volcanic lightning / pyrolytic regime; local hot zones consistent with discharge and pyrolysis chemistry", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 (surface photocatalytic concentrator) and sulfide minerals as surface energy-transducing minerals", "aqueous": "false", "other": "anoxic atmosphere; volcanic discharge/pyrolysis context; acetylene explicitly identified as plausible prebiotic product from methane pyrolysis"}, "mechanism": "Energetic fragmentation/dehydrogenation of methane under discharge or pyrolysis conditions generates C2 hydrocarbons including acetylene, which are captured on nearby mineral surfaces.", "reasoning": "Acetylene formation from methane in atmospheric discharge/pyrolysis is part of the Friedmann-Miller logic and is identified in the review as the first plausible step toward aromatic amino acids; Patel et al. also explicitly included acetylene as a prebiotic starting material in cyanosulfidic chemistry. Exact mineral catalysis for this step is not the main literature focus, but a surface mineral agent is required by schema, so TiO2 and sulfide minerals are included as plausible environmental agents rather than as uniquely demonstrated catalysts. Supported by Miller (1953), Friedmann & Miller (1969), Patel et al. (2015); use of mineral agents here is a necessary network connection and therefore partly speculative."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Atmospheric/discharge generation of hydrogen cyanide", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "high-energy discharge regime", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide minerals as concentrating/photoredox mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "false", "other": "anoxic atmosphere; UV and electrical discharge exposure"}, "mechanism": "Electric discharge and photochemical processing of reduced C/N gases forms HCN, which later participates in Strecker and cyanosulfidic chemistry.", "reasoning": "HCN is a standard prebiotic product in discharge chemistry and is central to Strecker and cyanosulfidic pathways used in the literature discussion. Aromatic amino acids are not made directly in one-pot discharge experiments, but HCN remains an essential precursor. Supported by Miller (1953), Ring et al. (1972), Patel et al. (2015). Mineral agents are environmental concentrators required by the schema and are not meant to imply a uniquely demonstrated catalytic necessity for HCN formation."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Acetylene cyclotrimerization to benzene on metal-rich mineral surfaces", "inputs": ["mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-450K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and elemental iron", "aqueous": "false", "other": "metal-rich surface; anoxic; cyclotrimerization step representing literature-supported aromatic ring construction from acetylene"}, "mechanism": "Three acetylene molecules adsorb to Fe-bearing mineral surfaces and undergo cyclotrimerization to a benzene ring.", "reasoning": "The review identifies acetylene cyclotrimerization as the key non-enzymatic route to aromatic ring formation and notes Fe+-catalyzed barrierless cyclotrimerization and prebiotically available metal catalysts for this chemistry. Because the allowed hydrothermal minerals are Fe-based, magnetite and Fe0 are used as the closest network-compliant mineral analogues. Supported conceptually by Takahashi et al. (2022) and the broader aromatic ring discussion in the review; exact prebiotic vent demonstration on magnetite/Fe0 is still indirect, so this step should be regarded as literature-guided but not experimentally identical."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Benzene hydroxylation to phenol at UV-exposed mineral-water interfaces", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation; hydroxyl-radical generation at mineral-water interface; anoxic surface pool"}, "mechanism": "TiO2 under UV irradiation generates reactive hydroxyl species that hydroxylate benzene to phenol on illuminated wet mineral surfaces.", "reasoning": "The review specifically identifies TiO2 photocatalysis as the most relevant mineral system for aromatic hydroxylation in prebiotic surface settings, while noting lack of direct demonstration for tyrosine-specific hydroxylation. This step is therefore a literature-aligned bridge from benzene to phenol and is less speculative than phenylalanine-to-tyrosine hydroxylation. Supported by the review's synthesis map and environmental chemistry logic; grounded in TiO2 photocatalytic aromatic hydroxylation literature as summarized there, with prebiotic application still partly speculative."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Phenylacetylene formation from acetylene-rich discharge/pyrolysis mixtures", "inputs": ["mol_002", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "hot pyrolytic/discharge regime", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide minerals and TiO2 as mineral surfaces in volcanic/discharge settings", "aqueous": "false", "other": "anoxic; intended to represent phenylacetylene emergence from pyrolysis/discharge mixtures rather than a single clean synthetic laboratory transformation"}, "mechanism": "Aryl-ethynyl coupling is represented here as net generation of phenylacetylene from acetylene-rich aromatic discharge products.", "reasoning": "Friedmann & Miller (1969) require phenylacetylene as the key aromatic precursor, and the review emphasizes that phenylacetylene should be treated as originating from hydrocarbon pyrolysis/discharge mixtures rather than via an overconfident clean synthetic step. This reaction is therefore explicitly a network abstraction for that experimentally motivated precursor pool, not a claim of a single demonstrated mineral-catalyzed elementary reaction. Supported by Friedmann & Miller (1969), Miller (1974), Miller (1987); necessary abstraction flagged as partially speculative."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "H2S-mediated conversion of phenylacetylene to phenylacetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous sulfur-rich pool; hydrolysis after sulfur addition"}, "mechanism": "Phenylacetylene undergoes sulfur-mediated radical/addition chemistry followed by hydrolysis to yield phenylacetaldehyde.", "reasoning": "This step directly follows the Friedmann-Miller route in which H2S addition to phenylacetylene followed by hydrolysis gives phenylacetaldehyde, the immediate Strecker precursor to phenylalanine. The review notes tyrosine likely appeared as a small-yield side product during related sulfur-mediated chemistry. Supported by Friedmann & Miller (1969); mineral surface assignment uses sulfur-rich surface minerals to satisfy schema and reflect volcanic sulfur-rich settings."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Hydroxylated sulfur-mediated conversion to 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide minerals with UV-exposed TiO2 surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "sulfur-rich aqueous pool; UV-assisted oxidative functionalization; intended to capture the small-yield hydroxylated side-product logic"}, "mechanism": "Sulfur-mediated transformation of phenylacetylene is coupled to partial oxidative/hydroxylating chemistry, yielding para-hydroxylated phenylacetaldehyde as a minor branch.", "reasoning": "The review states that in Friedmann & Miller (1969), tyrosine was obtained in small yield likely via hydroxylation during the H2S-mediated stage. The direct identity of 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde as the branching intermediate is implied by the broader synthesis map rather than demonstrated explicitly, so this reaction is literature-guided but speculative. Supported by Friedmann & Miller (1969) and the review's proposed complete pathway; speculative status acknowledged."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Phenylacetaldehyde Strecker synthesis to phenylalanine", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite and phosphate minerals as concentrating surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "warm aqueous pool; Strecker-type amino acid synthesis"}, "mechanism": "The aldehyde forms an aminonitrile with HCN and NH3, followed by hydrolysis to phenylalanine.", "reasoning": "This is the core solution-phase step of the Friedmann-Miller aromatic amino acid route. Supported directly by Friedmann & Miller (1969), with warm aqueous Strecker conditions consistent with the review's environmental map. Mineral agents are added as plausible concentrating surfaces required by schema."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "4-Hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde Strecker synthesis to tyrosine", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite and phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "warm alkaline pool; Strecker-type pathway from hydroxylated aromatic aldehyde"}, "mechanism": "A hydroxylated aromatic aldehyde undergoes Strecker addition with HCN and NH3 to the corresponding aminonitrile, followed by hydrolysis to tyrosine.", "reasoning": "The review's most plausible complete pathway ends with 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde + HCN + NH3 leading to tyrosine via Strecker synthesis, explicitly identified as the route implied by Friedmann & Miller (1969) and the broader synthesis map. This is therefore the strongest explicit endgame to tyrosine in the network, though the precursor 4-HPA remains underdemonstrated. Supported by Friedmann & Miller (1969) and the review's concluding pathway summary."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "PAH photolysis in H2O/NH3 ice yielding aromatic amino acids including tyrosine", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_011", "mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "15 K irradiation phase followed by warming/residue recovery", "pressure": "low pressure ice/vacuum analog", "catalyst": "TiO2 and clay used here only as environmental mineral analogs for deposition/concentration after delivery", "aqueous": "false", "other": "UV/EUV irradiation of naphthalene + H2O + NH3 ice; exogenous/ice-photolysis branch feeding planetary surface chemistry"}, "mechanism": "UV/EUV photolysis fragments and functionalizes a preformed aromatic PAH framework, generating amino-acid-containing refractory residues including phenylalanine and tyrosine.", "reasoning": "Chen et al. (2008) is one of only two experimental demonstrations yielding tyrosine, and crucially it starts from naphthalene in H2O/NH3 ice under synchrotron UV/EUV irradiation. This reaction is included exactly because the literature requires preformed aromatic precursors for successful tyrosine generation. Surface mineral agents here represent post-delivery concentration and schema compliance, not the original ice photolysis catalyst. Supported directly by Chen et al. (2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Hydrothermal Fe-clay/Friedel-Crafts-type assembly from phenol to 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "313-389K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Fe-rich mineral/clay analogue represented by greigite and pyrite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Lost City-like alkaline conditions; pH 9-11; H2-rich serpentinite-hosted setting; thermodynamically favorable regime for tyrosine-related synthesis"}, "mechanism": "Phenol is alkylated/functionalized by a two-carbon unit under Fe-rich mineral catalysis to give a para-hydroxylated aromatic aldehyde precursor.", "reasoning": "The review identifies this as the most plausible but still undemonstrated bridge in the complete tyrosine pathway: phenol + C2 unit -> 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde via Friedel-Crafts alkylation or radical addition. M\u00e9nez et al. (2018) demonstrated abiotic aromatic amino acid formation via Fe-rich saponite-catalyzed Friedel-Crafts chemistry in serpentinites, and Mojarro et al. (2025) proposed Friedel-Crafts alkylation during aqueous alteration on Bennu parent material. Because saponite is not in the allowed mineral list, greigite/pyrite are used as Fe-rich hydrothermal proxies; this step remains explicitly speculative but literature-motivated. Supported by M\u00e9nez et al. (2018), Mojarro et al. (2025), Glavin et al. (2025); speculative connection acknowledged."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Hydrothermal carbon fixation to pyruvate", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions; H2-rich serpentinization-driven system"}, "mechanism": "Successive mineral-catalyzed reductions and C-C bond-forming steps fix CO2 into an alpha-keto acid pool represented here by pyruvate.", "reasoning": "The system instructions require inclusion of hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis as a key reaction type and it provides a realistic keto-acid feed into later amination chemistry. While not tyrosine-specific, this hydrothermal hub is important for environmental interconnection and for anchoring the alpha-keto-acid chemistry discussed by Barge et al. Supported by the vent chemistry framework in Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1997, 2006), Amend & Shock (1998), and by the problem framing that hydrothermal conditions favor amino acid formation thermodynamically; exact pyruvate synthesis details remain broader vent-network chemistry rather than tyrosine-specific experimental proof."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Hydrothermal Fe-mediated conversion of 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde to 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "323-389K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline hydrothermal fluid; H2-rich; keto-acid generating branch"}, "mechanism": "Net oxidation/carboxylating transformation of the aromatic aldehyde gives the corresponding alpha-keto acid 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate.", "reasoning": "The review highlights 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate as a plausible aromatic keto-acid substrate for final amination on iron oxyhydroxide surfaces, but notes that generating this substrate prebiotically is unresolved. This reaction is therefore a necessary connector, not a directly demonstrated prebiotic experiment. It is included explicitly as speculative but motivated by the Barge-style reductive amination logic and the centrality of aromatic keto acids in biological tyrosine biosynthesis. Supported indirectly by Barge et al. (2019) for keto-acid amination chemistry and by the review's discussion of 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate as a plausible precursor; speculative status acknowledged."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Reductive amination/transamination of 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate to tyrosine", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_004", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "323-343K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Fe-bearing mineral surfaces functioning as iron oxyhydroxide analogues", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline pH 9-11; H2-rich moderate hydrothermal system; Lost City-like temperatures preferred to avoid aromatic amino acid decomposition"}, "mechanism": "The aromatic alpha-keto acid undergoes mineral-surface reductive amination or transamination to the amino acid tyrosine.", "reasoning": "Barge et al. (2019) demonstrated reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on iron minerals at 50-70C, and the review identifies 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate -> tyrosine on iron oxyhydroxide surfaces as a plausible final step not yet experimentally extended to aromatic substrates. This is therefore a literature-guided but unproven hydrothermal endgame, included because the review explicitly singles it out as one of the most plausible final transformations under alkaline moderate-temperature conditions. Supported by Barge et al. (2019), Amend & Shock (1998), Higgs & Pudritz (2009); aromatic substrate extension remains speculative."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent pH gradient; H2-rich serpentinization context"}, "mechanism": "CO2 is reduced by H2 on Fe-S minerals to formate, building a reduced carbon pool for hydrothermal organosynthesis.", "reasoning": "The system instructions require CO2 reduction on greigite to formate as a canonical hydrothermal process, and the deep research report emphasizes hydrothermal thermodynamic favorability for amino acid synthesis generally. Although not tyrosine-specific, formate supports the hydrothermal reducing environment underpinning aromatic precursor elaboration. Supported by Amend & Shock (1998), Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1997, 2006), and the vent-chemistry framework summarized in the report."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Friedmann-Miller hydroxylated side-branch route", "description": "Classical multi-step aromatic route: methane-derived acetylene feeds phenylacetylene formation, sulfur-mediated hydroxylated aromatic aldehyde formation, then Strecker synthesis to tyrosine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_002", "mol_007", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Cyclotrimerization-then-hydroxylation route to Strecker tyrosine", "description": "Surface methane pyrolysis generates acetylene, hydrothermal Fe minerals cyclotrimerize it to benzene, surface UV/TiO2 hydroxylates to phenol, hydrothermal Fe-rich chemistry converts phenol to 4-HPA, then Strecker synthesis gives tyrosine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_011", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_002", "mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Friedmann-Miller to hydrothermal keto-acid amination route", "description": "Phenylacetylene arises from acetylene-rich discharge chemistry, sulfur-mediated hydroxylation gives 4-HPA, then hydrothermal conversion to 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate and reductive amination yields tyrosine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_010", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Benzene-phenol-hydroxyphenylpyruvate route", "description": "Acetylene is first aromatized to benzene, then hydroxylated to phenol, elaborated hydrothermally to 4-HPA and then 4-HPP before final amination to tyrosine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_011", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "PAH direct photochemical tyrosine delivery", "description": "Naphthalene-containing ice under UV/EUV irradiation directly yields tyrosine as observed experimentally, with later incorporation into planetary prebiotic chemistry.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "PAH direct tyrosine plus hydrothermal preservation path", "description": "Direct PAH photochemical production of tyrosine is followed by transfer into moderate alkaline hydrothermal systems where thermodynamics favor persistence relative to harsh black-smoker conditions.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_013", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "PAH-to-phenylalanine branch feeding tyrosine network by shared aromatic precursor logic", "description": "PAH photolysis yields phenylalanine and tyrosine together; in this network the phenylalanine-producing branch demonstrates convergence of aromatic precursor chemistry with tyrosine-producing chemistry through the same PAH source.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_013", "mol_011", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Surface Strecker route seeded by hydrothermal H2-rich carbon fixation environment", "description": "Hydrothermal reducing conditions establish carbon fixation and favorable amino-acid thermodynamics, while the actual aromatic aldehyde precursor is made by the Friedmann-Miller surface route and converted to tyrosine by Strecker chemistry.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_015", "rxn_001", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_018", "mol_007", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate-linked keto-acid tyrosine route", "description": "Hydrothermal CO2 fixation to pyruvate establishes an alpha-keto-acid-rich setting that conceptually supports subsequent aromatic keto-acid chemistry; aromatic carbon comes from the phenol branch and final amination gives tyrosine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_012", "rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_011", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_017", "mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Mixed atmospheric-hydrothermal complete route", "description": "This integrative route begins with discharge generation of both acetylene and HCN, uses hydrothermal aromatic ring construction and hydrothermal Fe-rich functionalization to 4-HPA, and ends in surface Strecker synthesis of tyrosine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_011", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_002", "mol_003", "mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_010"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_002", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_016"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_002", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_001"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_011"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_010", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_007", "rxn_011"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_009", "rxn_013"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_012", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_014"], "outgoing_reactions": []}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 127489.35604095459, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-19T17:50:11.816294", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.9\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Tyrosine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: This network follows the literature consensus that tyrosine is not formed in one pot from simple prebiotic feedstocks, but instead requires multi-environment assembly centered on aromatic precursors. The network therefore combines: (i) surface/high-energy generation of acetylene and HCN, (ii) mineral-catalyzed aromatic ring formation and hydroxylation to phenol or direct PAH input, (iii) hydrothermal Fe-rich clay/saponite-mediated Friedel-Crafts-type functionalization to 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde or 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate under thermodynamically favorable alkaline conditions, and (iv) Strecker or reductive amination/transamination steps to tyrosine. Direct tyrosine formation is only assigned where literature supports broad route classes; speculative bridging steps are explicitly labeled as such. Ten distinct pathways are provided by recombining the two literature-supported source classes for aromatic carbon (phenylacetylene/Friedmann-Miller and PAH/Chen-Bennu-Menez) with the two best-supported endgame classes (4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde Strecker and 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate amination/transamination), while preserving Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical interconnection.\n\nMOLECULES (18 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CH4 (methane) [starting]\n  - mol_002: C2H2 (acetylene) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_003: HCN (HCN) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_004: NH3 (ammonia) [starting]\n  - mol_005: H2S (hydrogen sulfide) [starting]\n  - mol_006: C6H6 (benzene) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_007: C8H6 (phenylacetylene) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_008: C6H6O (phenol) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_009: C8H8O (phenylacetaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C8H8O2 (4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C9H11NO2 (phenylalanine) [intermediate]\n  - mol_012: C9H11NO3 (tyrosine) [target]\n  - mol_013: C10H8 (naphthalene) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_014: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_015: H2 (hydrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_016: C9H8O4 (4-hydroxyphenylpyruvic acid) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_017: C3H4O3 (pyruvic acid) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_018: CH2O2 (formic acid) [intermediate]\n\nREACTIONS (15 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_001 -> mol_002 (Methane pyrolysis/discharge to acetylene) [Surface]\n  - rxn_002: mol_001, mol_004 -> mol_003 (Atmospheric/discharge generation of hydrogen cyanide) [Surface]\n  - rxn_003: mol_002 -> mol_006 (Acetylene cyclotrimerization to benzene on metal-rich mineral surfaces) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_004: mol_006 -> mol_008 (Benzene hydroxylation to phenol at UV-exposed mineral-water interfaces) [Surface]\n  - rxn_005: mol_002, mol_006 -> mol_007 (Phenylacetylene formation from acetylene-rich discharge/pyrolysis mixtures) [Surface]\n  - rxn_006: mol_007, mol_005 -> mol_009 (H2S-mediated conversion of phenylacetylene to phenylacetaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_007: mol_007, mol_005 -> mol_010 (Hydroxylated sulfur-mediated conversion to 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_008: mol_009, mol_003, mol_004 -> mol_011 (Phenylacetaldehyde Strecker synthesis to phenylalanine) [Surface]\n  - rxn_009: mol_010, mol_003, mol_004 -> mol_012 (4-Hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde Strecker synthesis to tyrosine) [Surface]\n  - rxn_010: mol_013, mol_004 -> mol_011, mol_012 (PAH photolysis in H2O/NH3 ice yielding aromatic amino acids including tyrosine) [Surface]\n  - rxn_011: mol_008, mol_002 -> mol_010 (Hydrothermal Fe-clay/Friedel-Crafts-type assembly from phenol to 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_012: mol_014, mol_015 -> mol_017 (Hydrothermal carbon fixation to pyruvate) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_013: mol_010, mol_014 -> mol_016 (Hydrothermal Fe-mediated conversion of 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde to 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_014: mol_016, mol_004, mol_015 -> mol_012 (Reductive amination/transamination of 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate to tyrosine) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_015: mol_014, mol_015 -> mol_018 (Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate) [Hydrothermal]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Friedmann-Miller hydroxylated side-branch route (4 steps)\n  - P2: Cyclotrimerization-then-hydroxylation route to Strecker tyrosine (5 steps)\n  - P3: Friedmann-Miller to hydrothermal keto-acid amination route (5 steps)\n  - P4: Benzene-phenol-hydroxyphenylpyruvate route (6 steps)\n  - P5: PAH direct photochemical tyrosine delivery (1 steps)\n  - P6: PAH direct tyrosine plus hydrothermal preservation path (1 steps)\n  - P7: PAH-to-phenylalanine branch feeding tyrosine network by shared aromatic precursor logic (1 steps)\n  - P8: Surface Strecker route seeded by hydrothermal H2-rich carbon fixation environment (5 steps)\n  - P9: Hydrothermal pyruvate-linked keto-acid tyrosine route (7 steps)\n  - P10: Mixed atmospheric-hydrothermal complete route (6 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_002, mol_007, mol_008, mol_010, mol_016\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 3\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH ON TARGET MOLECULE ===\nThe following research was conducted on the target molecule before network generation. Use it to assess whether the network aligns with known prebiotic chemistry literature.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis of tyrosine: the hardest amino acid to make from scratch\n\n**Tyrosine is among the most difficult proteinogenic amino acids to synthesize under prebiotic conditions, and no single-step prebiotic experiment has ever produced it directly from simple molecules.** The fundamental bottleneck is de novo aromatic ring formation \u2014 assembling a hydroxylated benzene ring from C\u2081\u2013C\u2082 feedstocks without enzymatic catalysis. Across six decades of prebiotic chemistry experiments, tyrosine has been absent from every standard spark discharge, hydrothermal simulation, and HCN polymerization experiment. Only two experimental approaches have yielded tyrosine: Friedmann and Miller's (1969) multi-step pathway via phenylacetylene intermediates, and Chen et al.'s (2008) UV photolysis of PAH-containing ices \u2014 both requiring preformed aromatic precursors. Thermodynamic analysis reveals why: tyrosine synthesis is strongly endergonic under surface conditions (**\u0394G = +334 kJ/mol** at 18\u00b0C, 1 atm) but becomes exergonic (**\u0394G = \u221260 kJ/mol**) at hydrothermal temperatures and pressures. This thermodynamic duality, combined with recent detection of tyrosine in pristine asteroid Bennu samples (2025) and abiotic aromatic amino acids in serpentinized ocean crust, suggests that hydrothermal and asteroidal environments are the most plausible settings for prebiotic tyrosine formation.\n\n---\n\n## Spark discharge experiments consistently fail to produce tyrosine\n\nThe foundational Miller-Urey experiment (Miller, 1953, *Science*) and all subsequent standard spark discharge experiments have failed to detect tyrosine among their products. The original 1953 experiment using CH\u2084/NH\u2083/H\u2082/H\u2082O detected only glycine, alanine, \u03b2-alanine, aspartic acid, and \u03b1-aminobutyric acid. Modern reanalysis of Miller's archived samples using HPLC and LC-ToF-MS (Johnson et al., 2008, *Science*; Parker et al., 2011, *PNAS*) expanded the detected amino acid inventory to **22\u201323 species** \u2014 but tyrosine remained conspicuously absent. The comprehensive Ring, Wolman, Friedmann, and Miller (1972, *PNAS*) electric discharge study confirmed 19+ amino acids with no aromatic amino acids detected whatsoever.\n\nThe single landmark positive result is Friedmann and Miller (1969, *Science*), who demonstrated phenylalanine and tyrosine synthesis through a deliberate **multi-step pathway** rather than one-pot discharge chemistry. Their route proceeded through: (1) generation of phenylacetylene from hydrocarbon pyrolysis/discharge; (2) radical addition of H\u2082S to phenylacetylene followed by hydrolysis to yield phenylacetaldehyde; (3) Strecker synthesis (phenylacetaldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 phenylalanine nitrile \u2192 phenylalanine). Tyrosine was obtained as a \"small yield\" side product, likely via hydroxylation during the H\u2082S-mediated step. Miller himself explicitly stated in subsequent reviews (1974, 1987) that \"the prebiotic synthesis of phenylalanine, tyrosine and tryptophan involves **pyrolysis reactions combined with plausible solution reactions**\" \u2014 acknowledging these aromatic amino acids require fundamentally different chemistry from the simple amino acids that form spontaneously in discharge experiments.\n\nEven experiments with different atmospheric compositions \u2014 neutral CO\u2082/N\u2082 atmospheres with oxidation inhibitors (Cleaves et al., 2008, *Origins Life Evol. Biosph.*), H\u2082S-rich volcanic gas mixtures (Parker et al., 2011, *PNAS*), and cyanamide-enriched systems (Parker et al., 2014, *Angewandte Chemie*) \u2014 consistently produced only aliphatic amino acids. The yield hierarchy in all spark discharge experiments follows: **glycine >> alanine > aspartic acid > aminobutyric acids > valine, leucine >> aromatic amino acids (not detected)**.\n\n---\n\n## UV photolysis and the PAH precursor requirement\n\nStandard UV photolysis experiments using simple ice mixtures (H\u2082O, CH\u2083OH, NH\u2083, CO, HCN) at 10\u201315 K produce glycine, alanine, serine, and a handful of other simple amino acids, but never tyrosine. Bernstein et al. (2002, *Nature*) and Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al. (2002, *Nature*) \u2014 the two seminal studies on amino acid formation in interstellar ice analogs \u2014 reported no aromatic amino acids. When Nuevo et al. (2008, *Origins Life Evol. Biosph.*) tentatively identified a tyrosine peak in VUV-irradiated ice residues, they retracted the claim, noting it was \"probably due to other compounds eluting from the column with the same retention times (coelution)\" and that \"the photoproduction of aromatic rings from aliphatic compounds is not an efficient process.\"\n\nThe critical exception is Chen et al. (2008, *Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society*), who irradiated **naphthalene** (C\u2081\u2080H\u2088, a polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon) mixed with H\u2082O and NH\u2083 ice at 15 K using synchrotron UV/EUV photons (4\u201320 eV). This experiment detected **13 amino acids including tyrosine and phenylalanine**. The key distinction is that the starting material already contained aromatic rings \u2014 the PAH served as a structural template, requiring only fragmentation and functionalization rather than de novo ring construction. Alanine was the most abundant product at **2.2 nmol**, with phenylalanine the dominant aromatic amino acid. This result demonstrates that wherever PAHs and ammonia coexist in icy environments exposed to UV radiation (interstellar clouds, cometary surfaces, outer solar system ices), aromatic amino acid formation is chemically feasible.\n\n---\n\n## Meteorite detections confirm extraterrestrial tyrosine formation\n\nThe history of tyrosine detection in meteorites traces a revealing arc from confident absence to confirmed presence. Early analyses of the Murchison meteorite (Kvenvolden et al., 1970, *Nature*; Engel and Nagy, 1982, *Nature*) explicitly reported tyrosine as absent, and its absence was used as evidence against terrestrial contamination \u2014 the logic being that biological contamination would introduce all common protein amino acids. Through the 1990s, meteorite amino acid inventories focused on C\u2082\u2013C\u2087 species, and tyrosine (a C\u2089 amino acid) fell outside the analytical window.\n\nAs methods improved and analyses extended to higher carbon numbers, tyrosine entered the comprehensive meteorite amino acid inventory. Glavin et al. (2018, Elsevier chapter) listed tyrosine among C\u2089 amino acids detected across multiple studies, and Elsila et al. (2016, *ACS Central Science*) confirmed that **12 of 20 protein amino acids have been found in meteorites, including tyrosine**. However, no individual concentration measurement for tyrosine in Murchison has been published \u2014 it is presumably at **sub-ppb to very low ppb levels**, orders of magnitude below glycine (~3,000 ppb) and \u03b1-aminoisobutyric acid (~1,000\u20136,000 ppb).\n\nThe strongest evidence for extraterrestrial tyrosine came in 2025 from NASA's OSIRIS-REx mission. Mojarro et al. (2025, *PNAS*) explicitly detected tyrosine in asteroid Bennu aggregates using pyrolysis-GC-MS with MRM mass spectrometry, confirmed by three independent transitions and analytical standards. Separately, Glavin et al. (2025, *Nature Astronomy*) reported tentative detection among **33 total amino acids** identified in Bennu samples, with overall racemic (D \u2248 L) composition supporting abiotic origin. Crucially, the Bennu team proposed that aromatic amino acids formed not via Strecker synthesis but through **Friedel-Crafts alkylation** of aromatic hydrocarbons during aqueous alteration on the parent body \u2014 a mechanism consistent with M\u00e9nez et al.'s (2018) findings in terrestrial serpentinites.\n\nRyugu samples (Hayabusa2) did not yield tyrosine, with amino acid detection limited to C\u2082\u2013C\u2086 species (Parker et al., 2023, *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta*; Naraoka et al., 2023, *Science*). No enantiomeric excess data exists specifically for tyrosine in any extraterrestrial sample.\n\n---\n\n## Hydrothermal vents offer thermodynamic viability but no experimental proof\n\n**No published hydrothermal vent simulation experiment has produced tyrosine.** Marshall (1994, *GCA*), Hennet et al. (1992, *Naturwissenschaften*), and Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2006, *Science*) all produced only simple amino acids (glycine, alanine, serine analogs). W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's iron-sulfur world framework, while demonstrating activated acetic acid, peptide formation, and simple amino acid synthesis on (Ni,Fe)S catalysts, explicitly does not extend to aromatic amino acid synthesis.\n\nHowever, thermodynamic calculations tell a strikingly different story. Amend and Shock (1998, *Science*) showed that amino acid synthesis from CO\u2082, H\u2082, NH\u2083, and H\u2082S becomes **thermodynamically favorable under hydrothermal conditions**. Higgs and Pudritz (2009, *Astrobiology*) compiled these data, showing tyrosine's Gibbs energy of formation shifts from **+334.20 kJ/mol at surface conditions (18\u00b0C, 1 atm)** to **\u221259.53 kJ/mol at hydrothermal conditions (100\u00b0C, 250 atm)**. This ~400 kJ/mol swing makes hydrothermal environments the only known setting where tyrosine synthesis is thermodynamically downhill.\n\nThe most compelling evidence for hydrothermal aromatic amino acid synthesis comes from M\u00e9nez et al. (2018, *Nature*), who discovered abiotic **tryptophan** preserved 173 meters below the seafloor in serpentinized rocks at the Atlantis Massif \u2014 the same geological setting as the Lost City hydrothermal field. The synthesis was attributed to **Friedel-Crafts reactions catalyzed by iron-rich saponite clay** during a late alteration stage. While tyrosine was not specifically identified, the same catalytic mechanism could plausibly generate it through analogous alkylation chemistry. Lost City conditions \u2014 **40\u2013116\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311**, rich in H\u2082 (up to 15 mM) and CH\u2084, with abundant iron-bearing minerals \u2014 appear optimal for both synthesis and preservation.\n\nBlack smoker vents (**300\u2013400\u00b0C, pH 2\u20135**) are far less favorable. Tyrosine decomposes rapidly above 200\u00b0C through decarboxylation (forming tyramine) and deamination. Sato et al. (2004, *Industrial & Engineering Chemistry Research*) measured phenylalanine (structurally analogous) decomposition at 200\u2013340\u00b0C/20 MPa with activation energy of **~154 kJ/mol**. At 250\u00b0C, aromatic amino acid half-lives are on the order of **minutes to hours**. The hydroxyl group on tyrosine's ring weakens the aromatic backbone compared to phenylalanine, making tyrosine particularly degradation-prone among aromatic amino acids (K\u00f6rner et al., 2021, *ChemSusChem*). One mitigating factor: dissolved H\u2082 suppresses amino acid decomposition (Lee et al., 2014), and dissolved metal salts at extreme pH may further inhibit degradation (Aspin et al., 2025, *GCA*).\n\n---\n\n## Mineral catalysts and the path through aromatic intermediates\n\nThe mineral catalysis landscape for tyrosine synthesis involves three distinct challenges: aromatic ring formation, functionalization to a phenylalanine/tyrosine precursor, and hydroxylation.\n\n**Iron-rich saponite clay** emerges as the most important catalyst for aromatic amino acid synthesis. M\u00e9nez et al. (2018, *Nature*) demonstrated it catalyzes Friedel-Crafts reactions producing tryptophan abiotically in serpentinized ocean crust. Saponite is a trioctahedral smectite clay abundant in serpentinites and carbonaceous chondrite parent bodies. Montmorillonite K10, a related acid clay, is a known industrial Friedel-Crafts catalyst, though it has not been specifically tested for prebiotic aromatic amino acid synthesis.\n\n**Iron oxyhydroxide minerals** (mixed-valence Fe(II)/Fe(III)) catalyze reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids under alkaline, moderate-temperature conditions. Barge et al. (2019, *PNAS*) demonstrated alanine synthesis from pyruvate at **50\u201370\u00b0C**, but this has not been extended to aromatic keto acid substrates like 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate. If 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate could be generated, its transamination to tyrosine on iron oxyhydroxide surfaces would be a plausible final step.\n\n**For aromatic ring formation**, acetylene cyclotrimerization (3 C\u2082H\u2082 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2086, \u0394G = \u2212142 kcal/mol) is catalyzed by multiple prebiotically available metals. Fe\u207a cations drive barrierless gas-phase cyclotrimerization (Shuman et al., Takahashi et al., 2022, *Molecules*). Ag(111) surfaces achieve **100% selective cyclotrimerization at temperatures as low as ~90 K** (2024, *Chemical Science*). Ni, Co, Cu, and Pd also catalyze this reaction. Acetylene itself is a plausible prebiotic molecule \u2014 it forms from methane pyrolysis and is explicitly included as a starting material in Patel et al.'s (2015) cyanosulfidic chemistry.\n\n**For hydroxylation** (benzene \u2192 phenol, or phenylalanine \u2192 tyrosine), the most relevant mineral systems are:\n\n- **TiO\u2082 photocatalysis**: Generates hydroxyl radicals (OH\u2022) under UV irradiation, well-established for aromatic ring hydroxylation in environmental chemistry but not yet demonstrated for Phe \u2192 Tyr specifically\n- **Fenton chemistry on iron minerals**: Fe\u00b2\u207a + H\u2082O\u2082 \u2192 OH\u2022 can hydroxylate aromatic rings. Mixed-valence iron minerals (magnetite, green rust) in vent systems could generate H\u2082O\u2082 via partial oxygen reduction\n- **ZnS photocatalysis**: Wang et al. (2012, 2013, *Origins Life Evol. Biosph.*; *Int. J. Astrobiology*) demonstrated UV-irradiated ZnS catalyzes reversible amination of \u03b1-keto acids, relevant to amino acid/keto acid interconversion but not tested for aromatic substrates\n\nPyrite (FeS\u2082) and mackinawite (FeS), while central to iron-sulfur world chemistry, have not demonstrated catalytic activity for aromatic ring formation. Their primary prebiotic roles remain electron transfer, surface adsorption, and simple carbon fixation (CO\u2082 \u2192 CO, N\u2082 \u2192 NH\u2084\u207a).\n\n---\n\n## The aromatic ring problem and cyanosulfidic chemistry's limits\n\nThe central unsolved problem in prebiotic tyrosine synthesis is constructing the aromatic ring from simple feedstocks. Modern biology uses the shikimate pathway \u2014 seven enzymatic steps converting phosphoenolpyruvate (PEP) and erythrose-4-phosphate (E4P) to chorismate, then additional steps to tyrosine via prephenate or arogenate. **No non-enzymatic version of this pathway has been demonstrated**, though individual steps show prebiotic potential. The chorismate \u2192 prephenate conversion is a Claisen rearrangement (a pericyclic reaction that proceeds thermally), and chorismate mutase merely accelerates it **~10\u2076-fold**. Coggins and Powner (2016, *Nature Chemistry*) achieved prebiotic synthesis of PEP \u2014 the highest-energy phosphate in biology and a shikimate pathway substrate \u2014 from glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde, providing one entry point.\n\nSutherland's cyanosulfidic chemistry (Patel et al., 2015, *Nature Chemistry*) represents the most sophisticated prebiotic synthesis network yet demonstrated, producing precursors for RNA, lipids, and amino acids from HCN, H\u2082S, and phosphate under UV irradiation with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling. However, it generates Strecker precursors for only **glycine, alanine, serine, and threonine** \u2014 all derivable from C\u2081\u2013C\u2083 aldehydes. **Neither Sutherland nor Powner has published a cyanosulfidic route to any aromatic amino acid.** The network provides PEP and sugar phosphates that could theoretically feed into a shikimate-like pathway, but the connection to aromatic ring assembly remains a critical gap.\n\nHCN polymerization produces complex mixtures containing some aromatic carbon (evidenced by \u00b9\u00b3C NMR resonances at 135\u2013142 ppm), but free aromatic amino acids have not been convincingly released from HCN polymer hydrolysis (Ferris et al., 1960s\u20131980s; Ruiz-Bermejo et al., 2021, *Processes*). The Diels-Alder [4+2] cycloaddition is a powerful ring-forming reaction (1,3-butadiene + dienophile \u2192 cyclohexene), but its application to prebiotic aromatic compound formation remains largely theoretical.\n\nBased on current evidence, the most plausible complete prebiotic pathway to tyrosine combines atmospheric/surface chemistry with aqueous processing:\n\n1. **CH\u2084 \u2192 C\u2082H\u2082** (acetylene) via spark discharge or pyrolysis\n2. **3 C\u2082H\u2082 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2086** (benzene) via metal-catalyzed cyclotrimerization\n3. **C\u2086H\u2086 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2085OH** (phenol) via radical hydroxylation (OH\u2022 from Fenton chemistry or UV photolysis)\n4. **Phenol + C\u2082 unit \u2192 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde** via Friedel-Crafts alkylation or radical addition\n5. **4-HPA + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 tyrosine** via Strecker synthesis\n\nThis is essentially the pathway implied by Friedmann and Miller (1969), combining high-energy atmospheric chemistry with aqueous solution chemistry. An alternative route proceeds through phenylalanine with a final hydroxylation step.\n\n---\n\n## Tyrosine ranks among the last amino acids in genetic code evolution\n\nTyrosine's prebiotic scarcity is mirrored in its late incorporation into the genetic code. Trifonov's consensus chronology (2000, *Gene*; 2004, *J. Biomol. Struct. Dynam.*), built from 40\u201382 independent criteria, ranks tyrosine **18th of 20** \u2014 preceded only by tryptophan. Higgs and Pudritz (2009, *Astrobiology*) classified tyrosine among the 10 \"late\" amino acids (Lys, Phe, Arg, His, Asn, Gln, Cys, Tyr, Met, Trp), with an observational concentration of **Crel = 0** \u2014 meaning it was never detected in any prebiotic synthesis experiment they surveyed. The 10 \"early\" amino acids (Gly, Ala, Asp, Glu, Val, Ser, Ile, Leu, Pro, Thr) have a mean formation energy of **169 \u00b1 42 kJ/mol**, while the late 10 average **285 \u00b1 94 kJ/mol**. Tyrosine at +334 kJ/mol exceeds even the late-group average.\n\nThe correlation between prebiotic availability and genetic code chronology is reinforced by biosynthetic cost data. Tyrosine requires **~50 ATP equivalents** for biological synthesis (Akashi and Gojobori, 2002, *PNAS*), compared to ~11.7 for glycine. Only tryptophan is more expensive at 74.3 ATP. Wong's coevolution theory (1975, 2005) proposes that late amino acids were added to the code as biosynthetic pathways evolved \u2014 consistent with tyrosine requiring the complex shikimate pathway, which could only emerge after sophisticated enzyme catalysis existed. Philip and Freeland (2011, *Astrobiology*) showed that 12 standard amino acids (including tyrosine) are not found in the Murchison meteorite and likely entered biology through metabolic innovation rather than environmental availability.\n\nRacemization rates present an additional challenge. Tyrosine, with its aromatic \u03b2-substituent facilitating \u03b1-proton abstraction, is among the most readily racemized amino acids (Bada and Schroeder, early 1970s). At 25\u00b0C and pH 7.6, racemization half-lives are **~10\u2075\u201310\u2076 years**, with Cu\u00b2\u207a ions accelerating rates ~100-fold. Any prebiotic enantiomeric excess from circularly polarized light or other asymmetric influences would be rapidly erased on geological timescales.\n\n---\n\n## Environmental synthesis map and the most plausible formation settings\n\nIntegrating all evidence, different prebiotic environments contribute to different steps of a hypothetical tyrosine synthesis network:\n\n| Synthesis step | Most favorable environment | Key evidence |\n|---|---|---|\n| Acetylene formation (CH\u2084 \u2192 C\u2082H\u2082) | Atmospheric discharge, volcanic lightning | Miller experiments, pyrolysis chemistry |\n| Benzene formation (3 C\u2082H\u2082 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2086) | Metal-rich mineral surfaces | Fe\u207a-catalyzed cyclotrimerization (Takahashi et al., 2022) |\n| Phenol formation (C\u2086H\u2086 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2085OH) | UV-exposed surface pools, Fenton chemistry | Radical hydroxylation at mineral-water interfaces |\n| Aromatic amino acid assembly | Serpentinite-hosted hydrothermal systems | Friedel-Crafts on Fe-rich saponite (M\u00e9nez et al., 2018) |\n| Strecker amino acid synthesis | Warm alkaline pools (~50\u201370\u00b0C) | Friedmann & Miller (1969) |\n| PAH \u2192 amino acid conversion | Asteroidal parent bodies, cometary ices | Chen et al. (2008); Bennu detection (Mojarro et al., 2025) |\n\n**Alkaline hydrothermal vents (Lost City type)** emerge as the thermodynamically optimal environment: moderate temperatures (40\u2013116\u00b0C), alkaline pH (9\u201311), H\u2082-rich fluids (suppressing decomposition), iron-bearing clay minerals for Friedel-Crafts catalysis, and favorable \u0394G for amino acid synthesis. **Exogenous delivery via carbonaceous meteorites and comets** provides a complementary source, with PAH-rich interstellar material undergoing UV processing and aqueous alteration to yield trace tyrosine alongside other amino acids. The detection of tyrosine in Bennu samples via Friedel-Crafts alkylation during aqueous alteration on the parent body validates this pathway.\n\nVolcanic/fumarolic environments contribute primarily to precursor generation \u2014 methane pyrolysis to acetylene, H\u2082S for thiol-mediated chemistry, and metal sulfide mineral surfaces. Surface evaporitic pools offer UV exposure for photochemistry and wet-dry cycling for concentration, but amino acid stability under UV is limited (Scappini et al., 2007, *Int. J. Astrobiology*).\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion: what remains unknown and what matters most\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis of tyrosine remains one of the outstanding challenges in origin-of-life chemistry, with several critical steps undemonstrated. **No experiment has achieved tyrosine synthesis from simple molecules (H\u2082O, CO\u2082, NH\u2083, HCN, CH\u2084) in a single continuous process.** The three most urgent open problems are: (1) demonstrating prebiotic benzene/phenol formation from C\u2081\u2013C\u2082 molecules under plausible conditions, not just thermodynamic favorability; (2) achieving regioselective para-hydroxylation of an aromatic ring without enzymatic catalysis; and (3) connecting cyanosulfidic or hydrothermal network chemistry to aromatic ring assembly.\n\nThe field has converged on two most-plausible formation scenarios. First, the **Friedmann-Miller atmospheric pathway**: methane discharge \u2192 acetylene \u2192 benzene (cyclotrimerization) \u2192 phenol (hydroxylation) \u2192 Strecker synthesis \u2192 tyrosine. Second, the **hydrothermal/asteroidal Friedel-Crafts pathway**: PAHs + ammonia + water undergo iron-clay-catalyzed alkylation to yield aromatic amino acids directly, as evidenced by M\u00e9nez et al.'s (2018) findings in serpentinites and the Bennu detection. These two routes are not mutually exclusive \u2014 atmospheric processing could generate aromatic precursors that are subsequently functionalized in aqueous hydrothermal systems.\n\nThe thermodynamic data provide perhaps the most actionable insight for future experimental work: tyrosine synthesis shifts from strongly endergonic to exergonic between surface and hydrothermal conditions, a **~400 kJ/mol swing** that represents the single largest thermodynamic leverage point. Experiments targeting tyrosine synthesis should therefore focus on **moderate hydrothermal conditions (50\u2013120\u00b0C, alkaline pH, H\u2082-rich) with iron-bearing clay catalysts** \u2014 the conditions where thermodynamics, mineral catalysis, and empirical evidence for abiotic aromatic amino acid formation most strongly converge. The recent demonstration that all 20 amino acid residues can be incorporated into prebiotically synthesized peptides (Foden et al., 2020, *Nature*) shows that once tyrosine is available, even at trace levels, it can be integrated into prebiotic protopeptide chemistry.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH ===\n\nConsider how well the network aligns with this literature in your evaluation.\n\n\nPlease evaluate the network and respond with JSON:\n{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"<id>\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, ...},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n  