_002"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2", "molybdenite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "500-1000K local discharge/pyrolysis zones", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide mineral surfaces as environmental mineral interfaces", "aqueous": "false", "other": "volcanic lightning, spark discharge, or pyrolytic fumarolic setting; anoxic atmosphere"}, "mechanism": "High-energy fragmentation/dehydrogenation of methane produces C2 hydrocarbons including acetylene, which can be trapped on nearby mineral surfaces.", "reasoning": "Acetylene is explicitly identified in the literature as a plausible prebiotic product of methane pyrolysis/discharge and as a starting material relevant to cyanosulfidic and aromatic chemistry; the atmospheric precursor role follows Miller (1953), Friedmann and Miller (1969), and Patel et al. (2015). Exact mineral catalysis was not the focus of those studies, so TiO2 and molybdenite are included here as required surface mineral interfaces rather than as uniquely proven catalysts; this step is literature-grounded for product class but mineral assignment is connective and partially speculative."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Acetylene cyclotrimerization to benzene on metal-rich mineral surfaces", "inputs": ["mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["molybdenite", "TiO2"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "metal-rich mineral surface interface", "aqueous": "false", "other": "dry or thin-film surface setting; cyclotrimerization of 3 acetylene equivalents to benzene"}, "mechanism": "Surface-assisted [2+2+2] cyclotrimerization of acetylene generates an aromatic ring.", "reasoning": "The literature identifies acetylene cyclotrimerization as the key route to benzene from C2 feedstocks and cites metal-catalyzed feasibility, especially Fe+ and other metals, as a plausible prebiotic solution to the aromatic ring problem (Takahashi et al., 2022; Shuman et al., as summarized in the report). Because the required surface-mineral list does not include those exact metals, this network uses molybdenite/TiO2 as the mandated surface mineral context while preserving the literature route itself. This is a plausible but not directly demonstrated prebiotic Earth mineral implementation."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Discharge/pyrolytic generation of phenylacetylene from acetylene-rich hydrocarbon chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["molybdenite", "TiO2"], "conditions": {"temperature": "500-1000K local discharge/pyrolysis zones", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral surface trap and quench interface", "aqueous": "false", "other": "acetylene-rich volcanic lightning or pyrolysis chemistry; aromatic hydrocarbon byproduct formation"}, "mechanism": "High-energy hydrocarbon radical chemistry in acetylene-rich mixtures yields aromatic acetylenes including phenylacetylene.", "reasoning": "This step is aligned with Friedmann and Miller (1969), who used phenylacetylene as the crucial aromatic precursor and attributed it to pyrolysis/discharge hydrocarbon chemistry rather than to a benzene-plus-acetylene addition step. The network intentionally avoids the previously criticized unsupported benzene + acetylene -> phenylacetylene shortcut. Mineral agents here indicate the surface depositional environment required by the schema, but the chemistry itself is driven by discharge/pyrolysis as described by Friedmann and Miller (1969) and Miller (1974, 1987)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "H2S-mediated conversion of phenylacetylene to phenylacetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["stibnite", "molybdenite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide mineral surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "warm aqueous solution; radical addition of H2S followed by hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "Phenylacetylene undergoes sulfur-mediated addition chemistry, then hydrolytic conversion to the aldehyde.", "reasoning": "This is the core experimentally supported Friedmann-Miller branch. Friedmann and Miller (1969) reported that phenylacetylene treated through H2S-mediated chemistry followed by hydrolysis yields phenylacetaldehyde, enabling downstream Strecker chemistry. The use of sulfide minerals as agents is consistent with the sulfur-rich surface environment specified in the instructions, while the reaction class itself is directly based on Friedmann and Miller (1969)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Strecker synthesis of phenylalanine from phenylacetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite and phosphate-rich evaporitic setting", "aqueous": "true", "other": "warm alkaline pool; aminonitrile formation and hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "Phenylacetaldehyde forms an aminonitrile with HCN and NH3, which hydrolyzes to phenylalanine.", "reasoning": "This follows the explicit Strecker stage of the Friedmann-Miller pathway: phenylacetaldehyde + HCN + NH3 gives phenylalanine nitrile and then phenylalanine (Friedmann and Miller, 1969). The report also notes that warm alkaline pools are favorable for Strecker processing. Clay and phosphate minerals are included as required surface agents and as plausible concentrating/hydrolytic surfaces."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Minor tyrosine branch during hydroxylated Friedmann-Miller aromatic amino acid synthesis", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_014", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["stibnite", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide mineral plus clay concentration surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "same multi-step solution chemistry as phenylalanine-forming sequence; tyrosine appears in small yield side products"}, "mechanism": "A hydroxylated aromatic aldehyde branch forms within the sulfur-mediated aromatic precursor sequence and undergoes Strecker-type amino acid synthesis to tyrosine.", "reasoning": "Friedmann and Miller (1969) reported tyrosine in small yield as a side product in their deliberate multi-step aromatic amino acid synthesis, likely arising from hydroxylation during the H2S-mediated sequence before Strecker conversion. This reaction is intentionally framed as a minor branch rather than a clean one-step transformation, addressing prior overstatement. The exact hydroxylated aldehyde sequence was not fully resolved experimentally, so this node is literature-based but mechanistically only partially specified, consistent with Miller (1974, 1987)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "UV/Fenton-like hydroxylation of benzene to phenol", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2", "borate minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 photocatalyst", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed shallow pool; hydroxyl radical chemistry at mineral-water interface"}, "mechanism": "UV-activated TiO2 generates reactive oxygen species and hydroxyl radicals that hydroxylate the aromatic ring to phenol.", "reasoning": "The deep research report identifies benzene -> phenol via radical hydroxylation under UV photolysis or Fenton-type chemistry as a plausible necessary step in de novo terrestrial tyrosine synthesis, but not one directly demonstrated in a complete tyrosine pathway. TiO2 photocatalysis is specifically highlighted as relevant for aromatic hydroxylation. Therefore this step is retained as a literature-supported class of chemistry but explicitly speculative as a tyrosine-network connection (Chen et al., 2008 for UV aromatic functionalization context; report synthesis citing TiO2 environmental photocatalysis)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Hydrothermal Fe-clay Friedel-Crafts-like assembly of 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde from phenol and acetylene", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite", "pyrite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "313-389K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "iron-rich clay/mineral hydrothermal interface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Lost City-like alkaline serpentinizing system, pH 9-11, H2-rich; moderate-temperature late alteration conditions"}, "mechanism": "Aromatic ring alkylation/side-chain construction on iron-rich mineral-clay interfaces yields a para-hydroxylated aromatic aldehyde precursor.", "reasoning": "This reaction captures the literature-implied but not directly demonstrated hydrothermal bridge: phenol plus a C2 unit leading to 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde through Friedel-Crafts-like chemistry. M\u00e9nez et al. (2018) demonstrated abiotic tryptophan formation in serpentinized rocks via Fe-rich saponite-catalyzed Friedel-Crafts chemistry, and Mojarro et al. (2025) proposed analogous Friedel-Crafts alkylation during Bennu parent-body aqueous alteration for aromatic amino acids including tyrosine. However, no tyrosine-specific experimental hydrothermal synthesis of 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde has been published, so this step is explicitly speculative but literature-motivated. Greigite and pyrite are included as required hydrothermal mineral agents representing the iron-sulfur hydrothermal context; the catalytic precedent itself comes from iron-rich saponite clay in M\u00e9nez et al. (2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Hydroxylated aromatic Strecker synthesis of tyrosine from 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressu