n a reaction if you want to preserve network rigor\",\n        \"Replace biochemical identity steps with genuine condensation/polymerization chemistry\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.74,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"The network is topologically adequate and clearly built around literature-recognized difficulty in prebiotic tyrosine synthesis. It contains sufficient molecule and reaction nodes, several genuine hubs, and meaningful convergence around phenylacetaldehyde, 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde, and tyrosine. It also captures the two experimentally supported source classes from the literature: Friedmann-Miller multistep aromatic amino acid synthesis and Chen et al. PAH ice photolysis. These are major strengths. However, overall approval is limited by several structural and chemical issues. First, two reactions are identity/self-loop nodes (rxn_011 and rxn_012), which should not count as productive synthetic reactions in a bipartite synthesis network. Second, key hydrothermal and surface steps meant to bridge environmental gaps are speculative or under-specified, especially benzene hydroxylation and Fe-clay assembly of 4-hydroxyphenylacetaldehyde. Third, the network does not provide explicit mineral agents for every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction, despite that being a critical requirement; this weakens environmental interconnection quality. Fourth, while the literature supports hydrothermal thermodynamic favorability for tyrosine, it does not support direct hydrothermal production in the manner implied by stabilization reactions. Finally, the PAH photolysis route is strong but is better classified as astrochemical/exogenous rather than generic terrestrial surface chemistry. In summary, the network is scientifically informed and partially literature-aligned, but it is not yet viable as an approved complete synthesis network because several bridge reactions are speculative and some nodes are not true synthetic tran